1
00:00:45,128 --> 00:00:48,131
[water lapping]

2
00:01:04,690 --> 00:01:06,608
[man groaning]

3
00:01:10,153 --> 00:01:15,033
[gasps] Pull yourself together, Teddy.
Pull yourself together.

4
00:01:16,535 --> 00:01:18,453
[groans]

5
00:01:21,498 --> 00:01:22,499
It's just water.

6
00:01:24,543 --> 00:01:25,669
It's a lot of water.

7
00:01:26,962 --> 00:01:27,963
A lot of--

8
00:01:31,925 --> 00:01:32,926
Come on.

9
00:01:33,302 --> 00:01:35,637
[chains rattles]

10
00:01:57,284 --> 00:02:00,287
-You okay, boss?
-Yeah, I'm fine, I just…

11
00:02:01,538 --> 00:02:03,540
I just can't-- can't stomach the water.

12
00:02:07,878 --> 00:02:09,880
-You're my new partner.
-That's right.

13
00:02:11,673 --> 00:02:14,259
Not the best way to meet,
with my head halfway down the toilet.

14
00:02:14,801 --> 00:02:18,680
Doesn't exactly square with Teddy Daniels,
the man of the legend, I'll give you that.

15
00:02:18,764 --> 00:02:19,765
The legend?

16
00:02:20,432 --> 00:02:22,851
What the hell you boys smoking
over there in Portland, anyway?

17
00:02:23,226 --> 00:02:24,227
Seattle.

18
00:02:24,519 --> 00:02:26,146
I came from the office in Seattle.

19
00:02:29,274 --> 00:02:30,734
How long you been with the Marshals?

20
00:02:31,485 --> 00:02:32,486
Four years.

21
00:02:34,571 --> 00:02:35,864
So you know how small it is.

22
00:02:37,282 --> 00:02:38,283
Sure.

23
00:02:39,409 --> 00:02:41,662
What about you? You got a girl? Married?

24
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:44,164
I was.

25
00:02:56,593 --> 00:02:57,594
She died.

26
00:02:58,595 --> 00:03:01,264
-Jesus. I don't--
-Don't worry about it.

27
00:03:02,933 --> 00:03:05,519
There was a fire at the apartment building
while I was at work.

28
00:03:06,603 --> 00:03:07,646
Four people died.

29
00:03:08,438 --> 00:03:10,190
It was the smoke that got her,
not the fire.

30
00:03:10,273 --> 00:03:13,026
-See, that's-- that's important.
-I'm sorry, boss.

31
00:03:13,944 --> 00:03:16,738
Where are my goddamn cigarettes?

32
00:03:16,988 --> 00:03:18,824
Here, have one of mine.

33
00:03:19,408 --> 00:03:22,703
I could've sworn they were
in my jacket before I got on.

34
00:03:22,786 --> 00:03:24,913
Government employees will rob you blind.

35
00:03:27,958 --> 00:03:28,959
Thanks.

36
00:03:30,210 --> 00:03:32,838
They give you a briefing
about the institution before you left?

37
00:03:33,004 --> 00:03:34,923
All I know is it's a mental hospital.

38
00:03:36,675 --> 00:03:38,510
-For the criminally insane.
-[scoffs]

39
00:03:39,594 --> 00:03:41,805
Well, if it was just folks running
around hearing voices

40
00:03:41,888 --> 00:03:44,224
and chasing after butterflies,
they wouldn't need us.

41
00:03:54,693 --> 00:03:57,237
-Is that where we're headed?
-Yep.

42
00:03:57,904 --> 00:03:59,781
The other side
of the island is rock bluffs.

43
00:04:00,323 --> 00:04:02,242
All the way down to the edge of the water.

44
00:04:03,076 --> 00:04:06,413
The dock, it's the only way on, or off.

45
00:04:07,539 --> 00:04:10,000
We'll be casting off as soon
as you two are ashore.

46
00:04:10,542 --> 00:04:12,586
I'd appreciate it if you'd hurry up
about it.

47
00:04:13,211 --> 00:04:15,380
-Why?
-Storm's coming.

48
00:04:42,407 --> 00:04:43,992
Never seen a Marshal's badge before.

49
00:04:46,787 --> 00:04:49,748
I'm Deputy Warden McPherson, gentlemen.
Welcome to Shutter Island.

50
00:04:49,956 --> 00:04:51,374
I'll be the one taking you
up to Ashecliffe.

51
00:05:05,347 --> 00:05:07,682
Your boys seem a little on edge,
Mr. McPherson.

52
00:05:08,225 --> 00:05:09,976
Right now, Marshal, we all are.

53
00:05:54,604 --> 00:05:56,189
Electrified perimeter.

54
00:05:58,775 --> 00:05:59,776
How can you tell?

55
00:06:00,902 --> 00:06:02,612
I've seen something like it before.

56
00:06:31,975 --> 00:06:32,976
[McPherson] All right.

57
00:06:33,059 --> 00:06:35,353
You gentlemen will be accorded
all the help we can give.

58
00:06:35,937 --> 00:06:38,648
But during your stay,
you will obey protocol.

59
00:06:38,982 --> 00:06:39,983
Is that understood?

60
00:06:40,358 --> 00:06:41,359
Absolutely.

61
00:06:42,277 --> 00:06:45,155
The red brick building on your right
is Ward A, the male ward.

62
00:06:45,655 --> 00:06:48,366
Ward B, the female ward,
is the one on your left.

63
00:06:49,075 --> 00:06:51,786
Ward C, is that building on the bluffs.

64
00:06:52,120 --> 00:06:53,371
An old Civil War fort.

65
00:06:53,830 --> 00:06:55,832
The most dangerous patients
are housed there.

66
00:06:56,291 --> 00:06:58,168
Admittance to Ward C is forbidden,

67
00:06:58,376 --> 00:07:00,670
without the written consent
and physical presence

68
00:07:01,087 --> 00:07:02,631
of both myself and Dr. Cawley.

69
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:04,841
Is that understood?

70
00:07:06,384 --> 00:07:08,428
You act like insanity is catching.

71
00:07:11,723 --> 00:07:14,142
You are hereby required
to surrender your firearms.

72
00:07:16,478 --> 00:07:19,856
Mr. McPherson,
we are duly appointed federal marshals.

73
00:07:19,940 --> 00:07:22,525
We are required to carry our firearms
with us at all times.

74
00:07:22,609 --> 00:07:25,946
Executive order 319 of the Federal Code
of Penitentiaries states that

75
00:07:26,112 --> 00:07:27,656
when inside a penitentiary,

76
00:07:27,781 --> 00:07:30,533
the officers of that institution
have final authority.

77
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:36,456
Gentlemen, you will not get
through this gate with your firearms.

78
00:07:57,560 --> 00:08:00,313
Okay, now that the official stuff's done,
come on, boys.

79
00:08:00,897 --> 00:08:02,565
What do you say we go find Dr. Cawley?

80
00:08:03,024 --> 00:08:05,860
[crows cawing]

81
00:08:06,027 --> 00:08:07,737
[chains rattling]

82
00:08:15,036 --> 00:08:17,330
When did she escape? This prisoner?

83
00:08:17,580 --> 00:08:20,250
I'm afraid Dr. Cawley will have
to fill you in on the situation.

84
00:08:20,917 --> 00:08:21,918
Protocol.

85
00:08:22,002 --> 00:08:24,045
Correctional officers
at a mental institution,

86
00:08:24,129 --> 00:08:26,256
that's a weird sight,
if you don't mind me saying.

87
00:08:26,506 --> 00:08:28,508
[McPherson] It's the only facility
of its kind in the U.S.,

88
00:08:28,758 --> 00:08:29,759
even the world.

89
00:08:29,843 --> 00:08:32,137
We take only the most dangerous,
damaged patients,

90
00:08:32,512 --> 00:08:34,139
ones no other hospital can manage.

91
00:08:34,431 --> 00:08:36,057
And it's all due to Dr. Cawley.

92
00:08:36,516 --> 00:08:38,018
He's created something really unique here.

93
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:40,854
It's a hospital for people
our society normally considers

94
00:08:40,979 --> 00:08:41,980
beyond treatment.

95
00:09:06,713 --> 00:09:08,631
Top of his class at Johns Hopkins,
then Harvard…

96
00:09:09,132 --> 00:09:11,259
-[door buzzes open]
-[McPherson] IDs, gentlemen.

97
00:09:15,430 --> 00:09:16,639
Show your badges, gentlemen.

98
00:09:17,557 --> 00:09:21,227
Dr. Cawley's been consulted numerous times
by Scotland Yard,

99
00:09:21,644 --> 00:09:23,980
-MI5, the OSS.
-Why?

100
00:09:25,065 --> 00:09:26,066
What do you mean?

101
00:09:28,109 --> 00:09:31,488
What do intelligence agencies want
to consult a psychiatrist about?

102
00:09:31,571 --> 00:09:33,073
I guess you'll have to ask him.

103
00:09:34,491 --> 00:09:35,909
{\an8}[door buzzes open]

104
00:09:43,583 --> 00:09:45,085
-Marshal Daniels.
-Doctor.

105
00:09:46,169 --> 00:09:47,170
Marshal Aule.

106
00:09:48,171 --> 00:09:49,756
Thank you, Deputy Warden.
That will be all.

107
00:09:50,924 --> 00:09:53,468
Yes, sir. Pleasure, gentlemen.

108
00:09:55,220 --> 00:09:56,888
He had a lot to say about you.

109
00:09:57,013 --> 00:09:59,641
McPherson's a good man.
He believes in the work we do here.

110
00:10:00,183 --> 00:10:01,893
And what would that be, exactly?

111
00:10:02,602 --> 00:10:05,772
A moral fusion between law and order
and clinical care.

112
00:10:06,439 --> 00:10:08,983
[Chuck] Pardon me, Doc.
A what between what and what?

113
00:10:16,407 --> 00:10:18,201
Those paintings are quite accurate.

114
00:10:19,536 --> 00:10:22,664
Used to be the kind of patients
we deal with here were shackled

115
00:10:22,747 --> 00:10:24,082
and left in their own filth.

116
00:10:24,874 --> 00:10:25,875
They were beaten,

117
00:10:26,167 --> 00:10:28,419
as if whipping them bloody would drive
the psychosis out.

118
00:10:28,503 --> 00:10:30,630
We drove screws into their brains,

119
00:10:30,713 --> 00:10:33,967
we submerged them in icy water
until they lost consciousness or…

120
00:10:35,343 --> 00:10:36,344
even drowned.

121
00:10:37,137 --> 00:10:38,805
-And now?
-[Dr. Cawley] We treat them.

122
00:10:39,180 --> 00:10:40,515
Try to heal, try to cure.

123
00:10:41,349 --> 00:10:42,350
And if that fails,

124
00:10:42,433 --> 00:10:44,894
at least we provide them
with a measure of comfort in their lives.

125
00:10:45,061 --> 00:10:46,062
Calm.

126
00:10:46,563 --> 00:10:50,191
These are all violent offenders, right?
I mean…

127
00:10:51,025 --> 00:10:52,068
they've hurt people.

128
00:10:52,986 --> 00:10:55,655
-Murdered them in some cases.
-In almost all cases, yes.

129
00:10:56,823 --> 00:11:00,243
Then, personally, Doctor, I'd have to say,
screw their sense of calm.

130
00:11:02,579 --> 00:11:04,873
It's my job to treat my patients,
not their victims.

131
00:11:04,956 --> 00:11:06,124
I'm not here to judge.

132
00:11:06,374 --> 00:11:09,002
-So this female prisoner--
-Patient.

133
00:11:10,003 --> 00:11:11,004
Excuse me, patient,

134
00:11:11,754 --> 00:11:14,382
one Rachel Solando,

135
00:11:14,757 --> 00:11:17,010
escaped sometime in the last 24 hours.

136
00:11:17,093 --> 00:11:19,345
Last night, between ten and midnight.

137
00:11:19,429 --> 00:11:20,889
Is she considered dangerous?

138
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:24,309
You could say that.
She killed all three of her children.

139
00:11:25,643 --> 00:11:27,645
She drowned them in the lake
behind her house.

140
00:11:28,605 --> 00:11:31,357
She took them out one by one,
held their heads under till they died,

141
00:11:31,941 --> 00:11:33,568
then she brought them back inside
and arranged them

142
00:11:33,651 --> 00:11:34,986
around the kitchen table.

143
00:11:35,069 --> 00:11:36,946
She ate a meal there
before a neighbor dropped by.

144
00:11:40,283 --> 00:11:43,953
-And what about the husband?
-He died on the beaches of Normandy.

145
00:11:44,162 --> 00:11:45,413
She's a war widow.

146
00:11:45,997 --> 00:11:48,124
She starved herself
when she first came here.

147
00:11:48,249 --> 00:11:50,084
She insisted the children weren't dead.

148
00:11:56,674 --> 00:11:59,093
[distorted voices screaming]

149
00:12:01,012 --> 00:12:03,765
Sorry, Doctor, you don't happen
to have an aspirin, do you?

150
00:12:03,848 --> 00:12:05,141
[Dr. Cawley] Prone to headaches, Marshal?

151
00:12:05,516 --> 00:12:08,937
Sometimes, but today,
I'm a little more prone to seasickness.

152
00:12:09,020 --> 00:12:10,521
[Dr. Cawley] Ah, dehydration.

153
00:12:10,855 --> 00:12:12,357
-You all right, boss?
-Yeah.

154
00:12:12,565 --> 00:12:14,859
In that case, you're quite right.
The simpler the better.

155
00:12:15,276 --> 00:12:16,319
Thanks so much.

156
00:12:17,737 --> 00:12:19,948
Rachel still believes
the children are alive.

157
00:12:21,449 --> 00:12:24,035
She also believes this place is her home
in the Berkshires.

158
00:12:24,452 --> 00:12:25,453
[scoffs]

159
00:12:26,496 --> 00:12:28,539
-You're kidding me.
-She's, never once in two years,

160
00:12:28,665 --> 00:12:30,541
acknowledged that she's in an institution.

161
00:12:30,625 --> 00:12:33,836
She believes we're all deliverymen,
milkmen, postal workers.

162
00:12:34,420 --> 00:12:36,673
To sustain the delusion
that her children never died,

163
00:12:36,756 --> 00:12:39,050
she's created
an elaborate fictional structure,

164
00:12:39,175 --> 00:12:41,552
and she gives us all parts to play
in that fiction.

165
00:12:43,221 --> 00:12:45,139
So have you--
have you searched the grounds yet?

166
00:12:45,390 --> 00:12:47,600
The warden and his men scoured the island.

167
00:12:47,976 --> 00:12:49,143
Not a trace.

168
00:12:50,061 --> 00:12:52,981
And what's more disturbing is,
we don't know how she got out of her room.

169
00:12:54,691 --> 00:12:58,236
It was locked from the outside,
and the only window is barred.

170
00:13:01,447 --> 00:13:03,825
It's as if she evaporated straight
through the walls.

171
00:13:07,245 --> 00:13:08,788
[lock opening]

172
00:13:10,790 --> 00:13:13,793
I brought her right back here
after group therapy, locked her in,

173
00:13:14,669 --> 00:13:17,005
came back for a midnight round,
she was gone.

174
00:13:24,387 --> 00:13:28,308
Seriously, doctor, how is it possible
that the truth never gets through to her?

175
00:13:28,683 --> 00:13:31,227
I mean, she's in a mental institution,
right?

176
00:13:31,769 --> 00:13:33,730
Seems like something you'd notice
from time to time.

177
00:13:33,855 --> 00:13:35,982
How many pairs of shoes
are the patients given?

178
00:13:36,065 --> 00:13:37,066
Two pairs.

179
00:13:37,483 --> 00:13:41,279
Sanity's not a choice, Marshal.
You can't just choose to get over it.

180
00:13:42,405 --> 00:13:45,450
So, she left here barefoot?

181
00:13:46,284 --> 00:13:49,037
Come on, Doc, she couldn't get ten yards
in that terrain.

182
00:13:50,663 --> 00:13:51,664
[Dr. Cawley] Marshal?

183
00:14:10,767 --> 00:14:12,810
This is definitely Rachel's handwriting.

184
00:14:12,894 --> 00:14:15,855
I have no idea what
the law of four is, though.

185
00:14:15,938 --> 00:14:18,316
-It's not a psychiatric term?
-I'm afraid not.

186
00:14:18,733 --> 00:14:20,068
"Who is 67?"

187
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:22,695
Fuck if I know.

188
00:14:22,779 --> 00:14:25,239
I have to say that's quite close
to my clinical conclusion.

189
00:14:26,616 --> 00:14:28,201
Think it's just random scribblings?

190
00:14:28,618 --> 00:14:31,871
Oh, no, not at all. Rachel's smart.
Brilliant, in fact.

191
00:14:32,413 --> 00:14:33,873
This paper could be important.

192
00:14:33,998 --> 00:14:36,751
Excuse me, Doctor,
but we're gonna have to hold on to this.

193
00:14:36,959 --> 00:14:37,960
Of course.

194
00:14:38,669 --> 00:14:39,837
[man grunting]

195
00:14:40,213 --> 00:14:41,923
[Chuck]
And you say she had to come through here?

196
00:14:43,216 --> 00:14:46,427
[Dr. Cawley] After lights out,
the orderlies play cards in here.

197
00:14:47,553 --> 00:14:49,972
Last night, there were seven men sitting
at the base

198
00:14:50,056 --> 00:14:51,891
of those stairs playing stud poker.

199
00:14:52,517 --> 00:14:55,061
Yet somehow, Rachel managed
to slip past them.

200
00:14:56,187 --> 00:14:59,482
-Why?
-How? She turns invisible?

201
00:14:59,607 --> 00:15:00,608
[chuckles softly]

202
00:15:00,817 --> 00:15:02,026
Doctor, we're gonna need access

203
00:15:02,110 --> 00:15:04,070
to the personnel files
of all the medical staff.

204
00:15:04,153 --> 00:15:07,073
The nurses, the guards, the orderlies,
anyone who was working then.

205
00:15:07,156 --> 00:15:09,117
We'll take your request
under consideration.

206
00:15:09,242 --> 00:15:12,203
-[chuckles]
-This is not a request, Doctor.

207
00:15:12,620 --> 00:15:15,123
This is a federal facility
and a dangerous prisoner--

208
00:15:15,206 --> 00:15:16,958
-Patient.
-Patient…

209
00:15:17,417 --> 00:15:19,752
has escaped.
Now, you will comply

210
00:15:19,836 --> 00:15:21,671
-or--
-All I can say is, I'll see what I can do.

211
00:15:22,296 --> 00:15:25,049
Doctor, we're gonna need
to speak with the staff.

212
00:15:25,133 --> 00:15:26,134
Do you understand?

213
00:15:27,260 --> 00:15:29,512
I'll assemble them in the common room
after dinner.

214
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:33,307
<i>If you have any further questions,</i>
<i>feel free to join the deputy warden</i>

215
00:15:33,391 --> 00:15:34,475
<i>in the search.</i>

216
00:15:47,697 --> 00:15:49,198
[McPherson] It's 11 miles
to the nearest land

217
00:15:49,323 --> 00:15:50,366
and the water's freezing.

218
00:15:51,117 --> 00:15:53,411
Current was strong last night,
tide pushing in.

219
00:15:54,245 --> 00:15:55,872
She'd have drowned
or been crushed on the rocks,

220
00:15:55,955 --> 00:15:57,707
and her body would have washed back
up on shore.

221
00:16:02,128 --> 00:16:04,213
What about those caves down there?
Have you checked them?

222
00:16:05,298 --> 00:16:06,632
No way she could get there.

223
00:16:07,800 --> 00:16:10,219
The bases of those cliffs are covered
in poison ivy,

224
00:16:10,678 --> 00:16:14,432
live oak, sumac, a thousand plants
with thorns as big as my dick.

225
00:16:15,516 --> 00:16:17,685
You said yourself, Marshal,
she's got no shoes.

226
00:16:19,395 --> 00:16:21,522
[water lapping]

227
00:16:23,983 --> 00:16:26,569
All right, let's check the other side.

228
00:16:28,154 --> 00:16:30,031
[eagles screeching]

229
00:16:32,158 --> 00:16:34,744
-What's that tower?
-It's an old lighthouse.

230
00:16:35,786 --> 00:16:37,497
The guards already searched inside it.

231
00:16:40,416 --> 00:16:41,876
What's in there? More patients?

232
00:16:42,752 --> 00:16:44,128
Sewage treatment facility.

233
00:16:45,296 --> 00:16:48,549
It's getting dark soon.
I'm calling this off for tonight.

234
00:16:49,342 --> 00:16:50,343
Let's go, boys!

235
00:16:54,889 --> 00:16:56,516
[Teddy]
<i>You were on watch on the landing, huh?</i>

236
00:16:56,724 --> 00:17:00,144
Yeah, couldn't nobody get in or out
of their room on that corridor

237
00:17:00,228 --> 00:17:01,395
without me seeing.

238
00:17:02,021 --> 00:17:05,566
Okay, Rachel Solando,
who else does she have to pass

239
00:17:05,650 --> 00:17:06,776
to get down here?

240
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:15,660
Me. Glen Miga.

241
00:17:16,911 --> 00:17:18,079
Sir, I didn't see nothing.

242
00:17:18,454 --> 00:17:20,206
Yeah, and you were at your post all night?

243
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:22,583
Yeah, but I didn't see a thing.

244
00:17:25,336 --> 00:17:26,337
Glen.

245
00:17:28,339 --> 00:17:29,340
Glen.

246
00:17:32,218 --> 00:17:33,302
Tell me the truth.

