And it says in your file that…

496
00:34:10,298 --> 00:34:13,009
you tore her face off, didn't you?

497
00:34:13,176 --> 00:34:14,177
[pencil scribbling]

498
00:34:14,427 --> 00:34:17,931
Congratulations. No more normal for her.
Not ever again. No.

499
00:34:20,183 --> 00:34:22,811
Do you know what she was afraid of?

500
00:34:25,647 --> 00:34:28,650
-You.
-Could you stop that, please?

501
00:34:31,027 --> 00:34:32,028
Stop that!

502
00:34:33,321 --> 00:34:34,698
Please! Stop!

503
00:34:34,781 --> 00:34:36,449
Do you know a patient named
Andrew Laeddis?

504
00:34:36,616 --> 00:34:38,076
-Do you?
-No! No.

505
00:34:38,326 --> 00:34:40,370
-Boss. What's up?
-Fine.

506
00:34:40,495 --> 00:34:42,956
-I wanna go back. I wanna go.
-Peter! Come on!

507
00:34:43,123 --> 00:34:46,084
-I got him. Peter! Peter!
-Hey, Peter!

508
00:34:46,251 --> 00:34:47,252
Go back.

509
00:34:48,003 --> 00:34:49,418
-[Peter] I wanna go back.
-[guard] Come on, Peter.

510
00:34:49,493 --> 00:34:51,329
[Peter] I don't wanna see him.
I don't wanna see him anymore.

511
00:34:51,449 --> 00:34:52,610
[guard] It's okay. It's all right.

512
00:34:53,508 --> 00:34:55,218
[thunder rumbling]

513
00:34:59,389 --> 00:35:02,976
I'll never get out of here.
I'm not sure that I should.

514
00:35:04,686 --> 00:35:07,355
Excuse me for saying this, Miss Kearns.

515
00:35:07,439 --> 00:35:10,066
-Mrs.
-Mrs. Kearns.

516
00:35:11,901 --> 00:35:14,654
But you seem quite… quite normal.

517
00:35:14,779 --> 00:35:17,032
I mean, in-- in comparison
to the other patients here.

518
00:35:18,074 --> 00:35:21,703
Well, I have my dark days.
I suppose everybody does.

519
00:35:22,954 --> 00:35:26,166
The difference is most people don't kill
their husbands with an axe.

520
00:35:27,375 --> 00:35:28,376
Ah.

521
00:35:28,585 --> 00:35:31,296
Although, personally,
I think if a man beats you

522
00:35:31,379 --> 00:35:36,092
and fucks half the women he sees,
and no one will help you,

523
00:35:36,843 --> 00:35:39,638
axing him isn't the least
understandable thing you could do.

524
00:35:42,015 --> 00:35:44,142
-Maybe you shouldn't get out.
-[Bridget chuckles]

525
00:35:45,185 --> 00:35:46,811
What would I do if I did?

526
00:35:47,312 --> 00:35:49,230
[inhales] I don't know the world anymore.

527
00:35:49,689 --> 00:35:54,069
They say there are bombs
that can reduce whole cities to ash.

528
00:35:54,444 --> 00:35:59,741
And what do you call them? "Televisions",
voices and faces coming from a box.

529
00:36:00,784 --> 00:36:02,535
I hear enough voices already.

530
00:36:03,995 --> 00:36:05,747
What can you tell us about Rachel?

531
00:36:07,832 --> 00:36:08,833
Umm…

532
00:36:09,125 --> 00:36:12,087
Not much. She-- she keeps to herself.

533
00:36:12,379 --> 00:36:15,632
She believed her kids were alive.

534
00:36:16,549 --> 00:36:18,885
She thought she was still living
in the Berkshires,

535
00:36:18,968 --> 00:36:23,306
and we were all her neighbors,
the-- the milkmen,

536
00:36:23,682 --> 00:36:25,100
-postmen--
-Deliverymen.

537
00:36:26,643 --> 00:36:28,103
And Dr. Sheehan was there that night?

538
00:36:29,312 --> 00:36:32,982
Yes. Umm… he talked about anger.

539
00:36:35,694 --> 00:36:38,488
Tell me about him. What's he like?

540
00:36:41,032 --> 00:36:42,242
Ah… he's…

541
00:36:44,869 --> 00:36:46,037
okay. Nice.

542
00:36:48,123 --> 00:36:50,583
Not hard on the eyes,
as my mother would say.

543
00:36:51,084 --> 00:36:52,502
[Bridget chuckling]

544
00:36:53,503 --> 00:36:55,046
Did he ever make a pass at you?

545
00:36:56,297 --> 00:36:57,298
No.

546
00:36:57,966 --> 00:37:00,093
No, Dr. Sheehan's a good doctor,
he would never…

547
00:37:02,721 --> 00:37:03,722
Umm.

548
00:37:04,639 --> 00:37:06,641
Could I-- could I have a glass of water,
please?

549
00:37:06,933 --> 00:37:07,934
No problem.

550
00:37:23,241 --> 00:37:24,784
-Thank you, Marshal.
-[Chuck] Sure.

551
00:37:29,497 --> 00:37:32,125
[Teddy] I just have one more question
for you, Mrs. Kearns.

552
00:37:36,004 --> 00:37:38,256
Did you ever meet a patient
named Andrew Laeddis?

553
00:37:42,427 --> 00:37:43,428
No.

554
00:37:44,929 --> 00:37:46,097
[voice breaks] Never heard of him.

555
00:37:52,520 --> 00:37:53,563
[Teddy]<i> She was coached.</i>

556
00:37:54,230 --> 00:37:56,858
She used practically the same words
as Cawley and the nurse,

557
00:37:56,941 --> 00:37:59,736
-like she'd been told exactly what to say.
-[Chuck] Who's Andrew Laeddis?

558
00:38:04,949 --> 00:38:08,036
You asked every one of those patients
back there about him. Who is he?

559
00:38:13,124 --> 00:38:15,960
What the hell, boss?
I'm your partner, for Christ's sake.

560
00:38:16,586 --> 00:38:17,796
We just met, Chuck.

561
00:38:19,047 --> 00:38:22,550
You've been on the beat for a long time.
You've got a duty. You've got a career.

562
00:38:22,634 --> 00:38:23,635
What I'm doing…

563
00:38:25,553 --> 00:38:27,013
it's not exactly by the book.

564
00:38:28,473 --> 00:38:31,267
I don't-- I don't give a damn
about by-the-book, boss.

565
00:38:31,351 --> 00:38:33,353
I just wanna know
what the hell's going on.

566
00:38:38,399 --> 00:38:40,443
When this case came over the wires,

567
00:38:42,028 --> 00:38:44,572
I requested it specifically,
you understand?

568
00:38:45,365 --> 00:38:46,366
Why?

569
00:38:48,910 --> 00:38:49,994
Andrew Laeddis…

570
00:38:51,496 --> 00:38:53,706
he was the maintenance man
in the apartment building

571
00:38:53,790 --> 00:38:55,083
where my wife and I lived.

572
00:38:56,876 --> 00:38:57,877
Okay.

573
00:38:59,921 --> 00:39:01,548
He was also a firebug.

574
00:39:04,759 --> 00:39:06,678
Andrew Laeddis lit the match…

575
00:39:10,181 --> 00:39:12,559
that caused the fire that killed my wife.

576
00:39:21,276 --> 00:39:22,277
[guard] Let them out!

577
00:39:25,446 --> 00:39:28,241
-[Chuck] What happened to Laeddis?
-[Teddy] He got away with it.

578
00:39:28,783 --> 00:39:31,202
Laeddis got away with it
and then he disappeared.

579
00:39:31,286 --> 00:39:34,080
About a year ago,
I open up the paper and there he is.

580
00:39:34,497 --> 00:39:36,040
Ugly-looking son of a bitch.

581
00:39:36,332 --> 00:39:39,002
Huge scar from his right temple
down to his left lip.

582
00:39:39,085 --> 00:39:42,297
Eyes different colors.
Not the type of face you'd forget.

583
00:39:42,547 --> 00:39:45,466
He burned down a schoolhouse,
killed two people,

584
00:39:45,717 --> 00:39:47,427
said voices told him to do it.

585
00:39:47,594 --> 00:39:50,221
First, he went to prison,
then he got transferred here.

586
00:39:50,346 --> 00:39:52,140
-Then what?
-Then nothing.

587
00:39:52,640 --> 00:39:56,102
He vanished like he never existed.
No record whatsoever.

588
00:39:56,394 --> 00:39:57,979
Pretty sure he's not in Ward B.

589
00:39:58,104 --> 00:40:00,148
-That leaves Ward C.
-Or he could be dead.

590
00:40:00,398 --> 00:40:02,567
So could Rachel Solando, for that matter.

591
00:40:02,942 --> 00:40:05,069
Lot of places to hide a body here.

592
00:40:06,404 --> 00:40:08,865
Only one place no one would really notice.

593
00:40:20,793 --> 00:40:25,006
That patient, Bridget Kearns,
when she sent me for water,

594
00:40:25,089 --> 00:40:27,175
she said something to you back there,
didn't she?

595
00:40:28,051 --> 00:40:29,052
No.

596
00:40:31,095 --> 00:40:32,138
Come on, boss.

597
00:40:36,309 --> 00:40:37,310
She wrote it.

598
00:40:45,860 --> 00:40:48,780
[thunder rumbling]

599
00:40:53,284 --> 00:40:55,995
Boss! We gotta get indoors.

600
00:40:56,120 --> 00:40:58,289
It's turning into a fucking Kansas
out here.

601
00:40:58,456 --> 00:41:00,333
-[Teddy] Hold on.
-[Chuck] No, let's go!

602
00:41:03,461 --> 00:41:04,462
Watch out!

603
00:41:07,048 --> 00:41:08,049
Jesus!

604
00:41:10,009 --> 00:41:12,011
-Come on! Up there!
-[Teddy] Let's go!

605
00:41:14,931 --> 00:41:16,808
[Chuck] Get in there! Let's go!

606
00:41:20,728 --> 00:41:21,729
Boss!

607
00:41:28,820 --> 00:41:30,863
-[Teddy] God!
-Jesus Christ!

608
00:41:32,198 --> 00:41:34,158
[Teddy] Damn it. God!

609
00:41:42,959 --> 00:41:46,129
-You okay, boss?
-Yeah, I'm all right.

610
00:41:53,177 --> 00:41:57,390
So if Laeddis is here,
what are you gonna do about it?

611
00:42:00,435 --> 00:42:01,936
I'm not here to kill Laeddis.

612
00:42:10,570 --> 00:42:12,822
If it was my wife, I'd kill him. Twice.

613
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:28,629
[Teddy]<i> When we got through the gates</i>
<i>at Dachau, the SS guards surrendered.</i>

614
00:42:37,346 --> 00:42:40,808
The Kommandant tried to kill himself
before we got there, but…

615
00:42:42,560 --> 00:42:44,812
<i>he-- he botched it.</i>

616
00:42:46,981 --> 00:42:48,357
Took him an hour to die.

617
00:42:53,988 --> 00:42:57,492
When I went outside, I saw all the bodies
on the ground.

618
00:43:02,205 --> 00:43:03,247
<i>Too many to count.</i>

619
00:43:30,650 --> 00:43:32,026
Too many to imagine.

620
00:43:35,154 --> 00:43:36,155
So, yeah, the…

621
00:43:38,950 --> 00:43:41,994
the guards surrendered.
We took their guns and we lined them up.

622
00:43:42,537 --> 00:43:45,331
[indistinct shouting]

623
00:44:24,453 --> 00:44:25,705
[man choking, groaning]

624
00:44:27,081 --> 00:44:28,958
It wasn't warfare. It was…

625
00:44:31,294 --> 00:44:32,295
it was murder.

626
00:44:36,340 --> 00:44:38,759
Yeah, and I've--
I've had enough of killing.

627
00:44:41,679 --> 00:44:42,847
That's not why I'm here.

628
00:44:44,807 --> 00:44:46,267
So what is this all about?

629
00:44:48,853 --> 00:44:50,271
After Laeddis vanished…

630
00:44:52,106 --> 00:44:54,567
I started doing some checking
on Ashecliffe.

631
00:44:56,277 --> 00:44:59,697
A lot of people know about this place,
but no one wants to talk, you know?

632
00:44:59,822 --> 00:45:02,867
It's like… it's like they're scared
or something.

633
00:45:05,328 --> 00:45:07,872
You know, this place is funded
by a special grant…

634
00:45:09,290 --> 00:45:11,667
from The House Un-American
Activities Committee?

635
00:45:12,293 --> 00:45:15,463
HUAC? And how exactly
are we fighting the communists

636
00:45:15,588 --> 00:45:17,256
from an island in Boston Harbor?

637
00:45:18,466 --> 00:45:20,927
By conducting experiments on the mind.

638
00:45:22,553 --> 00:45:25,806
-At least, that's my guess.
-And you think that's going on here?

639
00:45:25,973 --> 00:45:27,850
Like I said, no one would talk, right?

640
00:45:28,476 --> 00:45:30,686
Till I found somebody
who used to be a patient here.

641
00:45:31,312 --> 00:45:35,233
Guy's name is George Noyce.
Nice college kid. Socialist.

642
00:45:35,733 --> 00:45:37,735
He gets offered some money
to do a psych study.

643
00:45:37,860 --> 00:45:40,238
-Guess what they were testing?
-Toothpaste.

644
00:45:40,488 --> 00:45:42,698
So, he starts seeing dragons everywhere.

645
00:45:42,865 --> 00:45:47,870
He almost beats his professor to death.
Ends up here in Ashecliffe, Ward C.

646
00:45:48,621 --> 00:45:51,958
They release him after one year, right?
And what does he do?

647
00:45:52,166 --> 00:45:54,835
Two weeks on the mainland,
he walks into a bar…

648
00:45:54,961 --> 00:45:57,004
-[claps hands together]
-…stabs three men to death.

649
00:45:57,838 --> 00:46:01,050
His lawyer pleads insanity.
But Noyce-- Noyce, he stands up

650
00:46:01,133 --> 00:46:04,720
in the courtroom and he--
he begs the judge for the electric chair.

651
00:46:04,804 --> 00:46:06,555
Anywhere but a mental hospital.

652
00:46:07,723 --> 00:46:09,850
Judge gives him life in Dedham Prison.

653
00:46:11,352 --> 00:46:13,354
-And you found him.
-Yeah, I found him.

654
00:46:14,230 --> 00:46:16,607
Well, he's… he's a mess.

655
00:46:18,401 --> 00:46:20,278
But it's pretty clear
from what he tells me.

656
00:46:20,569 --> 00:46:23,572
-What?
-They're experimenting on people here.

657
00:46:24,532 --> 00:46:25,616
I don't know, boss.

658
00:46:27,493 --> 00:46:30,621
-How do you believe a crazy guy?
-That's the beauty of it, isn't it?

659
00:46:30,871 --> 00:46:32,623
Crazy people,
they're the perfect subjects.

660
00:46:32,790 --> 00:46:34,667
They talk, nobody listens.

661
00:46:35,793 --> 00:46:36,919
I stood at Dachau.

662
00:46:37,670 --> 00:46:41,549
We-- we saw what human beings
are capable of doing to each other, right?

663
00:46:42,425 --> 00:46:45,011
For Christ's sakes, we fought
a goddamn war to stop them,

664
00:46:45,094 --> 00:46:47,346
and now-- now I find out
it may be happening here?

665
00:46:47,638 --> 00:46:49,307
On our soil? No.

666
00:46:51,183 --> 00:46:53,060
So, what are you really here to do, Ted?

667
00:46:54,520 --> 00:46:57,940
I'm gonna get the proof,
I'm gonna go back,

668
00:46:58,441 --> 00:47:01,902
and I'm gonna blow the lid off this place.
That's it.

669
00:47:03,404 --> 00:47:04,447
Wait a minute.

670
00:47:05,573 --> 00:47:07,825
You started asking around
about Ashecliffe,

671
00:47:08,409 --> 00:47:10,661
waiting for a chance to get out here,
and then, suddenly,

672
00:47:10,745 --> 00:47:11,912
they need a U.S. Marshal?

673
00:47:12,580 --> 00:47:13,581
Yeah.

674
00:47:13,748 --> 00:47:15,499
I got lucky. There was a patient escape.

675
00:47:15,583 --> 00:47:17,501
-It was the perfect excuse.
-No, no, no, boss.

676
00:47:17,585 --> 00:47:18,961
Luck doesn't work that way.

677
00:47:19,628 --> 00:47:21,339
The world doesn't work that way.

678
00:47:21,422 --> 00:47:24,550
They got an electrified fence
around a septic facility.

679
00:47:24,800 --> 00:47:27,470
Ward C is inside a Civil War fort?

680
00:47:28,054 --> 00:47:31,766
A Chief of Staff with ties to the OSS?
Funding from HUAC?

681
00:47:31,849 --> 00:47:33,225
I mean, Jesus Christ.

682
00:47:33,434 --> 00:47:36,354
Everything about this place stinks
of government ops.

683
00:47:36,437 --> 00:47:37,772
What if they wanted you here?

684
00:47:37,897 --> 00:47:39,774
-Bullshit.
-You were asking questions.

685
00:47:39,857 --> 00:47:40,858
-Bullshit! Bullshit!
-Bullshit.

686
00:47:40,983 --> 00:47:42,276
We came here for Rachel Solando.

687
00:47:42,360 --> 00:47:44,653
Where-- where's one shred of evidence
she even existed?

688
00:47:45,196 --> 00:47:47,656
There's no way they could've known
I'd be assigned to this case.

689
00:47:47,740 --> 00:47:49,450
-There's no way.
-What if while you were looking into them,

690
00:47:49,533 --> 00:47:50,743
they were looking into you?

691
00:47:51,452 --> 00:47:54,580
All they had to do was fake an escape
to get you here and now they have you.

692
00:47:54,663 --> 00:47:56,582
Now they have us both. Here! Now!

693
00:48:00,753 --> 00:48:02,421
[McPherson on megaphone]
<i>Marshals, are you out here?</i>

694
00:48:03,172 --> 00:48:04,757
<i>This is Deputy Warden McPherson.</i>

695
00:48:06,217 --> 00:48:09,303
-<i>Marshals!</i>
-How about that? They found us, huh?

696
00:48:09,387 --> 00:48:11,972
It's an island, boss.
They're always gonna find us.

697
00:48:13,349 --> 00:48:14,683
[McPherson]<i> I know you're in there.</i>

698
00:48:16,477 --> 00:48:20,022
We're getting off this goddamn island.
You and me. Come on!

699
00:48:24,318 --> 00:48:25,611
-Come on!
-Go, go!

700
00:48:35,913 --> 00:48:38,999
[McPherson] Get dried off.
Dr. Cawley wants to talk to you, now.

701
00:48:39,834 --> 00:48:42,837
And hurry up! This thing is turning
into a goddamn hurricane!

702
00:48:48,342 --> 00:48:52,012
I dropped those suits off to be cleaned.
They should be ready by tomorrow.

703
00:48:52,763 --> 00:48:54,473
That is if we all don't wash away first.

704
00:48:55,683 --> 00:48:59,812
You know, speaking of which, I'm afraid
your smokes are pretty much done for.

705
00:49:00,688 --> 00:49:01,689
So…

706
00:49:03,482 --> 00:49:04,900
This is our only choice, huh?

707
00:49:05,693 --> 00:49:08,571
Got something really nice in a prison gray
if that don't work for you.

708
00:49:08,946 --> 00:49:11,198
Now that you mention it,
these are just fine.

709
00:49:12,533 --> 00:49:15,661
That's why I must repeat my insistence
that all Ward C patients

710
00:49:15,744 --> 00:49:17,204
be placed in manual restraints.

711
00:49:18,038 --> 00:49:21,208
If the facility floods,
they'll drown. You know that.

712
00:49:21,834 --> 00:49:23,043
That would take a lot of flooding.

713
00:49:23,127 --> 00:49:25,045
[Dr. Cawley] We're on an island
in the middle of the ocean

714
00:49:25,129 --> 00:49:28,549
during a hurricane. A lot of flooding
seems like a distinct possibility.

715
00:49:28,674 --> 00:49:31,051
[doctor] It's a gamble, Stephen.
Say the power fails.

716
00:49:31,177 --> 00:49:32,344
There's a backup generator.

717
00:49:32,428 --> 00:49:35,139
And if that goes,
the cell doors will open.

718
00:49:36,599 --> 00:49:37,850
Where are they going to go?

719
00:49:39,018 --> 00:49:42,062
They can't just hop a ferry, scoot over
to the mainland and wreak havoc.

720
00:49:42,229 --> 00:49:43,230
[Dr. Naehring] You're quite right.

721
00:49:43,314 --> 00:49:46,233
They're far more likely
to wreak havoc right here on us.

722
00:49:47,234 --> 00:49:49,069
If they're manacled to the floor,
they'll die.

723
00:49:50,446 --> 00:49:51,989
This is 24 human beings.

724
00:49:52,823 --> 00:49:54,450
And you can live with that, can you?

725
00:49:54,533 --> 00:49:56,243
[Dr. Naehring]
Well, frankly, if it were up to me,

726
00:49:56,619 --> 00:49:59,955
I'd put all 42 in Wards A and B
in manual restraints as well.

727
00:50:00,331 --> 00:50:02,666
-Excuse me! Excuse me.
-[Dr. Cawley] Marshal.

728
00:50:02,958 --> 00:50:05,586
I-- I'm sorry, doctor.
I just have one quick question.

729
00:50:05,669 --> 00:50:07,963
-Yes, I'll be with you in a moment.
-When we spoke this morning

730
00:50:08,214 --> 00:50:09,798
about Rachel Solando's note…

731
00:50:09,965 --> 00:50:11,717
"The law of four." I love that.

732
00:50:11,800 --> 00:50:15,554
You said you had no idea what that
second line could refer to, correct?

733
00:50:16,472 --> 00:50:19,808
"Who is 67?"
Yes, I'm afraid I still don't.

734
00:50:20,059 --> 00:50:21,310
-None of us do.
-[Teddy] Uh-huh.

735
00:50:22,269 --> 00:50:23,354
Nothing comes to mind?

736
00:50:26,190 --> 00:50:27,191
Nothing?

737
00:50:31,445 --> 00:50:36,075
Because I believe I just heard you say
there are 24 patients in Ward C,

738
00:50:36,492 --> 00:50:39,036
and 42 patients in Wards A and B,

739
00:50:39,119 --> 00:50:42,540
which means there's a total of, what,
66 patients at this facility?

740
00:50:44,124 --> 00:50:45,292
That is correct, yes.

741
00:50:48,629 --> 00:50:51,006
Well, it seems to me
Rachel Solando was suggesting

742
00:50:51,799 --> 00:50:55,010
that you have a 67th patient, doctor.

743
00:50:56,512 --> 00:50:57,680
But I'm afraid we don't.

744
00:50:58,639 --> 00:51:00,516
This is ridiculous.
What are they doing here?

745
00:51:00,641 --> 00:51:02,351
We're doing our goddamn job.

746
00:51:03,102 --> 00:51:05,271
Didn't McPherson tell you the good news?

747
00:51:06,897 --> 00:51:08,357
No. What's the good news, doctor?

748
00:51:09,441 --> 00:51:10,568
Rachel's been found.

749
00:51:12,236 --> 00:51:13,237
She's here.

750
00:51:14,780 --> 00:51:15,781
Safe and sound.

751
00:51:28,002 --> 00:51:29,253
There's not a mark on her.

752
00:51:33,507 --> 00:51:34,592
Who are these men?

753
00:51:38,387 --> 00:51:39,763
Why are they in my house?

754
00:51:40,055 --> 00:51:44,435
Police officers, Rachel.
They… have a few questions.

755
00:51:48,147 --> 00:51:49,148
Ma'am…

756
00:51:52,651 --> 00:51:55,404
there has been a sighting
of a known communist…

757
00:51:56,071 --> 00:51:58,907
subversive in this area,
passing out literature.

758
00:52:01,076 --> 00:52:02,077
Here?

759
00:52:04,413 --> 00:52:05,497
In this neighborhood?

760
00:52:06,123 --> 00:52:07,541
Yes, I'm afraid so.

761
00:52:09,335 --> 00:52:12,379
Now if you could tell us
what you did yesterday, where you were,

762
00:52:12,963 --> 00:52:15,132
it would really help us narrow
down our search.

763
00:52:16,759 --> 00:52:17,760
Yes. Um…

764
00:52:20,721 --> 00:52:21,889
Well, I…

765
00:52:24,975 --> 00:52:27,102
I made breakfast for Jim and the children.

766
00:52:29,521 --> 00:52:30,522
And then, I…

767
00:52:32,775 --> 00:52:34,777
packed Jim's lunch and he left.

768
00:52:38,614 --> 00:52:40,741
Then, I sent the children off to school.

769
00:52:45,746 --> 00:52:46,747
And then…

770
00:52:53,420 --> 00:52:56,256
I decided to take a long swim in the lake.

771
00:53:03,514 --> 00:53:04,515
I see.

772
00:53:08,602 --> 00:53:09,603
And after that?

773
00:53:14,483 --> 00:53:16,151
[inhales deeply] Um…

774
00:53:17,986 --> 00:53:19,029
After that…

775
00:53:29,123 --> 00:53:30,249
I thought of you.

776
00:53:36,880 --> 00:53:40,801
I'm-- I'm sorry, ma'am. I--
I don't know what you're talking about.

777
00:53:43,846 --> 00:53:46,432
Don't you know how lonely I've been, Jim?

778
00:53:52,646 --> 00:53:53,647
You're gone.

779
00:53:57,985 --> 00:53:58,986
You're dead.

780
00:54:04,491 --> 00:54:06,076
I cry every night.

781
00:54:07,661 --> 00:54:08,662
[sobs]

782
00:54:12,166 --> 00:54:14,251
How am I supposed to survive?

783
00:54:16,044 --> 00:54:17,796
-God.
-[Rachel crying]

784
00:54:27,723 --> 00:54:30,768
Rachel, it'll be all right.

785
00:54:34,188 --> 00:54:35,814
I'm so sorry, but every…

786
00:54:37,941 --> 00:54:40,569
everything's gonna be all right. Okay?

787
00:54:42,696 --> 00:54:43,822
I buried you.

788
00:54:46,533 --> 00:54:49,411
I buried an empty casket.
Your body rained down lumps

789
00:54:49,495 --> 00:54:52,790
of flesh splashing into the sea,
eaten by sharks.

790
00:54:56,960 --> 00:54:59,254
My Jim's dead, so who the fuck are you?

791
00:55:03,050 --> 00:55:04,635
Who the fuck are you?

792
00:55:05,302 --> 00:55:06,553
-Who are you?
-[guard] Hey, hey, hey, hey.

793
00:55:06,637 --> 00:55:08,013
-Who are you?
-It's okay. Rachel. It is okay.

794
00:55:08,096 --> 00:55:11,683
-[guard] It's all right.
-[Rachel] Let me go! No! Get off!

795
00:55:12,518 --> 00:55:14,394
-[guard] Rachel, it's okay.
-[Dr. Cawley] Look at me, look at me.

796
00:55:14,603 --> 00:55:16,313
-[Rachel crying]
-[Dr. Cawley] Shh.

797
00:55:16,605 --> 00:55:17,815
-[lightning strikes]
-[thunder rumbling]

798
00:55:17,898 --> 00:55:20,859
I'm sorry about that.
I-- I didn't want to interrupt.

799
00:55:20,943 --> 00:55:22,903
I thought she might tell you something.
But,

800
00:55:23,320 --> 00:55:26,949
we found her down by the lighthouse,
skipping stones.

801
00:55:27,324 --> 00:55:29,660
We've no idea how she got out, but,

802
00:55:29,827 --> 00:55:32,120
I'm gonna have to ask you
to go down into the basement.

803
00:55:32,204 --> 00:55:33,997
There's food, water, and cots.

804
00:55:34,081 --> 00:55:37,209
It's the safest place to be,
when the hurricane hits.

805
00:55:41,630 --> 00:55:43,173
Are you all right? You look pale.

806
00:55:43,799 --> 00:55:45,342
I'm fine. It's just…

807
00:55:47,219 --> 00:55:48,762
[Chuck] Boss, are you okay?

808
00:55:49,847 --> 00:55:52,182
It's just so, so goddamn bright, isn't it?

809
00:55:52,432 --> 00:55:54,643
Photosensitivity, headaches, sometimes.

810
00:55:54,810 --> 00:55:57,771
-Marshal, are you having a migraine?
-[Teddy] I'll be all right.

811
00:55:59,857 --> 00:56:01,567
-[Teddy] Ah.
-[thunder rumbling]

812
00:56:01,650 --> 00:56:03,277
[Chuck] Come on, come on, I got you.

813
00:56:04,278 --> 00:56:05,737
-[coughs]
-[Chuck] What's wrong with him?

814
00:56:06,405 --> 00:56:08,031
Take these, Marshal.
Couple of hours,

815
00:56:08,172 --> 00:56:09,972
-you'll be as clear as a bell.
-[Chuck] What's wrong with him?

816
00:56:10,056 --> 00:56:10,993
He's having a migraine.

817
00:56:11,076 --> 00:56:13,287
Imagine someone sawed open your head,
filled it with razors,

818
00:56:13,370 --> 00:56:15,914
and shook it as hard as they could.
Take the pills, Marshal.

819
00:56:16,164 --> 00:56:18,292
-I don't-- I don't want the pills.
-It'll stop the pain.

820
00:56:18,375 --> 00:56:20,085
Marshal, take the pills.

821
00:56:24,214 --> 00:56:25,632
He's going to need to lie down.

822
00:56:26,300 --> 00:56:27,968
-[lightning striking]
-[thunder rumbling loudly]

823
00:56:32,055 --> 00:56:32,973
Oh, God.

824
00:56:33,056 --> 00:56:34,497
[man]
There's broken glass all over the floor.

825
00:56:34,597 --> 00:56:36,101
-Make sure the meds are locked up.
-Watch your back.

826
00:56:36,184 --> 00:56:37,519
[nurse]
Make sure everything's okay in Ward B.

827
00:56:37,686 --> 00:56:40,731
[indistinct clamor]

828
00:56:44,776 --> 00:56:47,404
-[Chuck] Over here. All right, boss.
-Yeah, that's it.

829
00:56:47,487 --> 00:56:48,488
-[guard] You have him?
-[Chuck] Yes.

830
00:56:48,697 --> 00:56:49,865
[guard] Careful. All right.

831
00:56:52,117 --> 00:56:54,202
Could be worse right now.
He'll be all right.

832
00:57:00,751 --> 00:57:01,752
Who is that?

833
00:57:02,336 --> 00:57:04,671
[guard] Him? That's the warden.

834
00:57:07,507 --> 00:57:09,092
Don't you worry about him, all right?

835
00:57:09,760 --> 00:57:11,678
Come on. Lay back. Lay back.

836
00:57:15,974 --> 00:57:19,186
He looks like an ex-military prick, huh?

837
00:57:19,269 --> 00:57:21,313
Well, you know what?
I ain't gonna argue with you on that one.

838
00:57:29,655 --> 00:57:30,781
[bell tolling]

839
00:57:39,122 --> 00:57:40,248
[bell tolling]

840
00:57:43,043 --> 00:57:46,254
[woman speaking German]

841
00:57:48,006 --> 00:57:49,174
[bell tolling]

842
00:58:01,186 --> 00:58:02,354
[bell tolling]

843
00:58:14,449 --> 00:58:15,701
[bell tolling]

844
00:58:21,206 --> 00:58:22,374
[bell tolling]

845
00:58:47,691 --> 00:58:49,151
[little girl] You should have saved me.

846
00:58:52,029 --> 00:58:54,156
You should have saved all of us.

847
00:58:58,243 --> 00:59:00,120
[classical music playing]

848
00:59:00,328 --> 00:59:03,206
[indistinct clamor]

849
00:59:21,475 --> 00:59:23,018
[Laeddis laughing]

850
00:59:23,310 --> 00:59:25,103
Hey, buddy.

851
00:59:27,355 --> 00:59:29,566
-Hey.
-Laeddis.

852
00:59:31,693 --> 00:59:32,694
Yeah.

853
00:59:38,075 --> 00:59:39,076
My…

854
00:59:43,663 --> 00:59:44,664
my buddy.

855
00:59:46,208 --> 00:59:47,334
No hard feelings, right?

856
00:59:52,172 --> 00:59:53,173
Yeah.

857
00:59:54,758 --> 00:59:55,842
No hard feelings.

858
01:00:09,815 --> 01:00:11,233
A little something for later.

859
01:00:15,654 --> 01:00:17,864
'Cause I know how much you need it.

860
01:00:19,950 --> 01:00:23,120
[clock ticking]

861
01:00:24,287 --> 01:00:25,831
The clock's ticking, my friend.

862
01:00:26,998 --> 01:00:28,250
We're running out of time.

863
01:00:29,626 --> 01:00:31,128
[clock ticking]

864
01:00:32,587 --> 01:00:33,922
[woman screaming]

865
01:00:39,261 --> 01:00:40,345
Give me a hand here.

866
01:01:03,326 --> 01:01:04,911
I could get into trouble.

867
01:01:33,231 --> 01:01:34,232
I'm dead.

868
01:01:37,611 --> 01:01:38,904
I'm so sorry.

869
01:01:40,697 --> 01:01:42,365
Why didn't you save me?

870
01:01:43,783 --> 01:01:47,621
I tried. I-- I wanted to.
But by the time I got there,

871
01:01:48,330 --> 01:01:49,331
it was too late.

872
01:02:11,519 --> 01:02:12,520
See?

873
01:02:15,899 --> 01:02:17,108
Aren't they beautiful?

874
01:02:34,334 --> 01:02:36,002
[thunder rumbling]

875
01:02:43,468 --> 01:02:45,345
[door opening]

876
01:03:12,372 --> 01:03:14,416
Why are you all wet, baby?

877
01:03:17,294 --> 01:03:18,378
Laeddis isn't dead.

878
01:03:20,380 --> 01:03:21,381
He isn't gone.

879
01:03:23,133 --> 01:03:24,134
He's still here.

880
01:03:26,970 --> 01:03:27,971
I know.

881
01:03:29,055 --> 01:03:30,307
You need to find him, Teddy.

882
01:03:31,224 --> 01:03:33,310
You need to find him,
and you kill him dead.

883
01:03:44,529 --> 01:03:47,407
[Dolores] Shh.

884
01:03:51,328 --> 01:03:52,370
It's okay.

885
01:03:59,753 --> 01:04:01,171
Shhh.

886
01:04:02,395 --> 01:04:03,548
[Nurse Marino] Security, head to Ward A.

887
01:04:03,631 --> 01:04:04,716
-Okay?
-[guard] Ward A. I got it.

888
01:04:04,841 --> 01:04:06,551
-[man] Security
-[man 1] The generator room's flooded.

889
01:04:07,469 --> 01:04:09,429
-[guard] Ward A. Ward A.
-See what we need in Ward B.

890
01:04:10,096 --> 01:04:11,097
[Nurse Marino] Let's go.

891
01:04:11,598 --> 01:04:12,974
You okay, boss?

892
01:04:15,852 --> 01:04:17,228
This goddamn migraine.

893
01:04:17,979 --> 01:04:21,608
The backup generator's failed.
The whole place has gone crazy.

894
01:04:23,485 --> 01:04:24,486
What do you want to do?

895
01:04:26,446 --> 01:04:28,573
[siren going off]

896
01:04:29,157 --> 01:04:30,992
[indistinct clamor]

897
01:04:31,117 --> 01:04:34,120
-Christ.
-[guard] Dan? Relax. Nope, nope, nope.

898
01:04:34,204 --> 01:04:36,664
You don't wanna do that. Put it down.
Now. Put it down.

899
01:04:36,748 --> 01:04:39,376
Grab him, grab him, grab him, grab him!
Get him, get him!

900
01:04:44,339 --> 01:04:46,549
[guard] You need to go find him
'cause he needs to be here.

901
01:04:47,467 --> 01:04:49,469
You think the whole electrical system
is fried?

902
01:04:50,220 --> 01:04:52,222
I'd say it's a good possibility, yeah.

903
01:04:52,972 --> 01:04:54,682
All the electronic security.

904
01:04:55,060 --> 01:04:57,018
-Always running? Why's it always you?
-[Teddy] The fences, the gates,

905
01:04:57,102 --> 01:04:58,103
the doors.

906
01:04:58,186 --> 01:04:59,187
[guard] Come on.

907
01:04:59,270 --> 01:05:03,149
Nice day for a stroll, don't you think?
To Ward C, for example.

908
01:05:03,650 --> 01:05:05,360
[car drove off]

909
01:05:05,819 --> 01:05:06,820
Come on.

910
01:05:06,903 --> 01:05:08,655
[Chuck]
Maybe we'll run into Andrew Laeddis.

911
01:05:13,952 --> 01:05:16,454
[Teddy]
The guy I told you about, George Noyce?

912
01:05:16,996 --> 01:05:19,457
He told me this is where they keep
the worst ones.

913
01:05:19,791 --> 01:05:21,835
Guys even the other inmates are scared of.

914
01:05:24,504 --> 01:05:26,297
Did Noyce give you anything
on the layout?

915
01:05:26,673 --> 01:05:27,674
Not really.

916
01:05:28,133 --> 01:05:30,510
All he remembered was people screaming
day and night,

917
01:05:30,593 --> 01:05:33,221
no windows and iron bars everywhere.

918
01:05:33,388 --> 01:05:34,389
[man] Watch your head!

919
01:05:36,808 --> 01:05:39,686
[indistinct clamor]

920
01:05:49,320 --> 01:05:51,739
[man shouting in distance]

921
01:05:54,993 --> 01:05:56,369
-Jesus Christ!
-Jesus.

922
01:05:57,078 --> 01:05:58,746
First time on Ward C, huh?

923
01:06:00,165 --> 01:06:01,499
-Yeah.
-Yeah. Yeah.

924
01:06:01,958 --> 01:06:05,170
-We heard stories, but--
-Trust me, son, you haven't heard shit.

925
01:06:06,171 --> 01:06:08,381
We got most of the bugsies locked
down now,

926
01:06:08,631 --> 01:06:10,341
but some of them are still loose.

927
01:06:10,633 --> 01:06:13,386
And if you see one, don't try
to restrain him yourselves.

928
01:06:13,470 --> 01:06:15,722
These fuckers will kill you. Clear?

929
01:06:16,890 --> 01:06:18,850
All right, get your asses moving then.
Go on.

930
01:06:21,519 --> 01:06:23,688
[man laughing menacingly in distance]

931
01:07:01,100 --> 01:07:02,352
[man shouting in distance]

932
01:07:16,658 --> 01:07:17,659
He's here.

933
01:07:21,871 --> 01:07:25,166
Laeddis. I can feel him.

934
01:07:28,086 --> 01:07:29,087
[screams]

935
01:07:29,629 --> 01:07:30,964
Tag! You're it!

936
01:07:32,966 --> 01:07:33,967
Ted!

937
01:07:42,976 --> 01:07:44,602
Hey! Hey!

938
01:07:46,145 --> 01:07:47,146
[Chuck] Teddy.

939
01:08:12,338 --> 01:08:14,924
-Ahh!
-[Teddy groans]

940
01:08:29,188 --> 01:08:30,189
Listen to me.

941
01:08:31,733 --> 01:08:34,360
Listen, I don't wanna leave here,
all right?

942
01:08:35,111 --> 01:08:36,821
I mean, why would anybody want to?

943
01:08:37,447 --> 01:08:40,700
We hear things here
about the outside world.

944
01:08:41,034 --> 01:08:44,329
-About atolls, about H-bomb tests.
-[Chuck] Teddy, where are you?

945
01:08:44,537 --> 01:08:46,581
You know how a hydrogen bomb works?

946
01:08:46,664 --> 01:08:49,834
-I know. With hydrogen! With hydrogen.
-That's funny.

947
01:08:49,917 --> 01:08:52,837
-Boss!
-Other bombs explode, right?

948
01:08:53,671 --> 01:08:55,214
-But not the hydrogen bomb.
-[pants]

949
01:08:55,381 --> 01:09:00,678
It implodes, creating an explosion
to the thousandth, the millionth degree!

950
01:09:01,262 --> 01:09:02,889
-Do you get it?
-Yeah! Yeah.

951
01:09:03,014 --> 01:09:04,515
-Do you?
-I get it, I get it!

952
01:09:04,599 --> 01:09:05,600
[Chuck] Let him go!

953
01:09:05,933 --> 01:09:06,934
-[Teddy groans]
-screams]

954
01:09:09,520 --> 01:09:10,521
[Chuck] No!

955
01:09:16,694 --> 01:09:18,821
-[Teddy groaning]
-[inmate choking]

956
01:09:19,906 --> 01:09:21,783
[Chuck] No! No!

957
01:09:23,242 --> 01:09:24,243
What are you doing?

958
01:09:25,286 --> 01:09:27,872
Jesus Christ, Teddy. Jesus!

959
01:09:28,373 --> 01:09:31,918
You got Billings?
What the fuck's the matter with you guys?

960
01:09:32,293 --> 01:09:33,378
Catch them, not kill them!

961
01:09:33,461 --> 01:09:35,963
-He jumped us.
-[guard] You, give me a hand with him.

962
01:09:36,464 --> 01:09:38,675
We've gotta get him to the infirmary.
Goddamn it.

963
01:09:38,966 --> 01:09:42,553
No, no! Not you, not you.
Take a walk. Come on.

964
01:09:43,262 --> 01:09:45,181
Cawley's gonna have
my goddamn balls for this.

965
01:10:16,629 --> 01:10:18,798
[man whispers] Laeddis.

966
01:10:34,772 --> 01:10:36,399
[loud footsteps running]

967
01:10:38,985 --> 01:10:40,236
[man whispers] Laeddis.

968
01:10:40,528 --> 01:10:45,241
[groaning]

969
01:10:45,700 --> 01:10:49,620
[indistinct chanting]

970
01:10:51,706 --> 01:10:53,958
[man] Stop me, please,

971
01:10:54,375 --> 01:10:55,835
before I kill more.

972
01:10:58,004 --> 01:11:00,339
Stop me before I kill more.

973
01:11:00,840 --> 01:11:02,550
[man whispers] Laeddis.

974
01:11:06,596 --> 01:11:10,224
[man screaming]

975
01:11:10,850 --> 01:11:12,685
[man 1] Please, please.

976
01:11:17,023 --> 01:11:18,649
[man 2] I see you all.

977
01:11:19,734 --> 01:11:22,820
[man whispers] Laeddis.

978
01:11:29,535 --> 01:11:34,665
You told me I'd be free of this place.
You promised.

979
01:11:36,793 --> 01:11:38,127
You lied.

980
01:11:38,711 --> 01:11:39,754
Laeddis.

981
01:11:45,593 --> 01:11:47,011
-Laeddis?
-[man laughs]

982
01:11:48,763 --> 01:11:50,181
[man] That's pretty damn funny.

983
01:11:52,517 --> 01:11:54,811
-Your voice.
-Don't you recognize it?

984
01:11:56,312 --> 01:11:57,855
After all the talks we had?

985
01:11:59,273 --> 01:12:01,025
After all the lies you told me?

986
01:12:01,484 --> 01:12:02,735
Let me see your face.

987
01:12:03,736 --> 01:12:05,029
They say I'm theirs now.

988
01:12:06,864 --> 01:12:08,324
They say I'll never leave here.

989
01:12:10,409 --> 01:12:11,953
Your match is about to go out.

990
01:12:15,122 --> 01:12:17,458
-Let me see your goddamn face! Now!
-Why?

991
01:12:18,334 --> 01:12:19,794
So you can lie to me more?

992
01:12:20,670 --> 01:12:22,713
-This isn't about the truth.
-Yes, it is.

993
01:12:23,214 --> 01:12:25,341
-It's about exposing the truth.
-It's about you!

994
01:12:26,926 --> 01:12:28,135
And Laeddis.

995
01:12:29,762 --> 01:12:30,930
That's all it's ever been about.

996
01:12:32,723 --> 01:12:34,350
I was incidental.

997
01:12:35,518 --> 01:12:36,602
A way in.

998
01:12:39,772 --> 01:12:40,773
George…

999
01:12:41,524 --> 01:12:42,608
George Noyce.

1000
01:12:43,526 --> 01:12:44,527
No.

1001
01:12:44,777 --> 01:12:48,155
-It's not possible. You can't be here.
-You like it?

1002
01:12:50,283 --> 01:12:51,826
Who did this to you, George?

1003
01:12:52,285 --> 01:12:53,286
You did.

1004
01:12:54,120 --> 01:12:55,121
What the hell do you mean?

1005
01:12:55,788 --> 01:12:59,250
All your talk. All your fucking talk.
And I'm back in here because of you.

1006
01:12:59,792 --> 01:13:02,128
George, how did-- how did they get you
out of Dedham, huh?

1007
01:13:02,461 --> 01:13:04,922
However this happened,
I-- I'm gonna find a way to fix this,

1008
01:13:05,006 --> 01:13:06,591
-you understand me?
-I'll never get out now.

1009
01:13:07,091 --> 01:13:09,594
I got out once. Not twice, never twice.

1010
01:13:09,677 --> 01:13:11,470
Just tell me how they got you here.

1011
01:13:11,679 --> 01:13:14,265
They knew! Don't you get it?

1012
01:13:15,057 --> 01:13:17,685
Everything you were up to.
Your whole plan.

1013
01:13:18,644 --> 01:13:22,189
This is a game. All of this, is for you.

1014
01:13:22,982 --> 01:13:24,609
You're not investigating anything.

1015
01:13:25,276 --> 01:13:27,445
You're a fucking rat in a maze.

1016
01:13:28,946 --> 01:13:32,325
Georgie, George, you're wrong.
You're wrong.

1017
01:13:33,367 --> 01:13:34,368
Really?

1018
01:13:35,036 --> 01:13:36,412
Been alone much since you got here?

1019
01:13:38,539 --> 01:13:40,207
I mean, I've been with my partner.

1020
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:42,418
You never worked with him before,
have you?

1021
01:13:45,087 --> 01:13:47,506
He's a-- he's a U.S. Marshal. He's--

1022
01:13:47,590 --> 01:13:49,759
You never worked with him before,
have you?

1023
01:13:53,179 --> 01:13:57,058
George, look, I-- I know people.
I-- I trust this man.

1024
01:14:02,146 --> 01:14:03,522
Then, they've already won.

1025
01:14:07,026 --> 01:14:08,027
Fuck.

1026
01:14:12,740 --> 01:14:15,952
And they're gonna take me
to the lighthouse.

1027
01:14:17,536 --> 01:14:19,455
They're gonna cut into my brain.

1028
01:14:20,873 --> 01:14:24,168
And I'm only here because of you!

1029
01:14:25,211 --> 01:14:27,421
George, I'm…
I'm gonna get you out of here.

1030
01:14:27,505 --> 01:14:29,924
You're not going to the lighthouse.
You're not.

1031
01:14:30,049 --> 01:14:32,802
You can't dig out the truth
and kill Laeddis at the same time.

1032
01:14:32,885 --> 01:14:35,680
You gotta make a choice.
You understand that, don't you?

1033
01:14:36,847 --> 01:14:39,433
-I'm not here to kill anyone.
-Liar!

1034
01:14:39,892 --> 01:14:42,687
I'm not gonna kill him, I swear to you!
I swear.

1035
01:14:43,229 --> 01:14:44,230
She's dead.

1036
01:14:45,564 --> 01:14:46,816
She-- let her go.

1037
01:14:48,734 --> 01:14:49,735
Let her go.

1038
01:14:51,153 --> 01:14:53,823
[Dolores] Tell him, Teddy. Tell him why.

1039
01:14:57,118 --> 01:14:58,786
[George]
You gotta do it. There's no other way.

1040
01:15:00,329 --> 01:15:01,872
-Let her go.
-Tell him about the day

1041
01:15:01,998 --> 01:15:04,542
-you brought me my locket.
-[George] You gotta do it!

1042
01:15:05,001 --> 01:15:08,587
How I told you my heart
was breaking and you asked me why.

1043
01:15:08,713 --> 01:15:11,382
She's fucking with your head.

1044
01:15:11,465 --> 01:15:13,342
And I told you it was from happiness.

1045
01:15:13,426 --> 01:15:15,803
She's gonna kill you.
She's gonna kill you.

1046
01:15:19,015 --> 01:15:22,143
You wanna uncover the truth?
You gotta let her go.

1047
01:15:24,353 --> 01:15:26,063
-I can't.
-You have to let her go!

1048
01:15:26,147 --> 01:15:28,024
I can't! I can't.

1049
01:15:34,905 --> 01:15:36,741
Then, you'll never leave this island.

1050
01:15:43,205 --> 01:15:44,206
Dolores.

1051
01:15:51,380 --> 01:15:52,757
He's not in this ward.

1052
01:15:55,217 --> 01:15:58,220
He was transferred… out of here.

1053
01:16:00,389 --> 01:16:01,974
If he's not in Ward A,

1054
01:16:02,850 --> 01:16:05,019
there's only one place he can be.

1055
01:16:11,150 --> 01:16:12,193
The lighthouse.

1056
01:16:19,992 --> 01:16:20,993
[George] Hey…

1057
01:16:23,496 --> 01:16:24,497
God help you.

1058
01:16:33,923 --> 01:16:36,759
[Chuck] Boss, we got problems.
McPherson and Cawley are in the building.

1059
01:16:37,927 --> 01:16:39,678
They heard an orderly went batshit
on a patient.

1060
01:16:39,887 --> 01:16:42,431
They're looking all over the place for him
and they're on their way to the roof.

1061
01:16:42,515 --> 01:16:44,433
Let's get the hell out of here. This way.

1062
01:16:47,603 --> 01:16:49,355
Just keep going. We belong here.

1063
01:16:53,150 --> 01:16:55,444
[Teddy grunts]

1064
01:16:59,782 --> 01:17:00,783
What happened to you?

1065
01:17:01,617 --> 01:17:03,119
-What do you mean?
-I mean,

1066
01:17:03,702 --> 01:17:04,703
where were you?

1067
01:17:05,579 --> 01:17:09,458
After we got that guy to the infirmary,
I took a little detour to patient records.

1068
01:17:10,626 --> 01:17:11,627
Did you ever find Laeddis?

1069
01:17:12,670 --> 01:17:14,547
No. No, I never found him.

1070
01:17:14,630 --> 01:17:17,133
Well, I got the next best thing.
His intake form.

1071
01:17:17,633 --> 01:17:19,802
It was the only thing in his files.
There's no session notes,

1072
01:17:19,885 --> 01:17:23,055
no incident reports, no photographs,
just this. It was weird.

1073
01:17:23,681 --> 01:17:24,974
Here. Take a look.

1074
01:17:26,183 --> 01:17:27,268
I'll look at it later.

1075
01:17:29,520 --> 01:17:30,521
What's the matter, boss?

1076
01:17:31,522 --> 01:17:32,815
I'll look it over later, that's all.

1077
01:17:36,110 --> 01:17:39,280
-Ashecliffe's that way.
-I'm not going to Ashecliffe.

1078
01:17:40,990 --> 01:17:42,324
I'm going to that lighthouse.

1079
01:17:42,992 --> 01:17:45,327
I'm gonna find out
what the fuck is happening on this island.

1080
01:17:59,508 --> 01:18:00,509
There it is.

1081
01:18:01,760 --> 01:18:05,472
Damn. We're too far south.
We're gonna have to double back.

1082
01:18:05,890 --> 01:18:07,600
There's no way we could cross
those rocks.

1083
01:18:08,142 --> 01:18:09,894
There could be a way
behind those trees.

1084
01:18:09,977 --> 01:18:12,479
Maybe, maybe a path that goes
around the rocks and leads over

1085
01:18:12,563 --> 01:18:14,481
-to the lighthouse, come on.
-Boss, wait, wait, what are we doing?

1086
01:18:14,565 --> 01:18:16,066
We got the intake form.

1087
01:18:16,650 --> 01:18:19,486
It's proof there's a 67th patient,
which they said, repeatedly,

1088
01:18:19,570 --> 01:18:20,571
doesn't exist.

1089
01:18:21,906 --> 01:18:24,992
I'm getting to that lighthouse.
You understand?

1090
01:18:27,328 --> 01:18:29,079
What the hell can I say to you
to stop you?

1091
01:18:29,163 --> 01:18:31,123
Why-- why would you want to, Chuck? Why?

1092
01:18:31,540 --> 01:18:33,417
Because climbing down there when it's dark

1093
01:18:33,500 --> 01:18:36,128
is a thin step short of suicide,
that's why.

1094
01:18:36,795 --> 01:18:37,796
Okay.

1095
01:18:38,589 --> 01:18:40,174
Maybe you better sit this one out then.

1096
01:18:41,717 --> 01:18:43,510
You brought me into this, boss,

1097
01:18:44,011 --> 01:18:46,055
and now we're trapped here on this rock,

1098
01:18:46,138 --> 01:18:48,849
on this island, with no one
to rely on but each other.

1099
01:18:48,933 --> 01:18:50,893
And now you're, you're acting like--

1100
01:18:50,976 --> 01:18:52,353
Like what? Like what?

1101
01:18:52,937 --> 01:18:53,979
How am I acting?

1102
01:18:58,609 --> 01:19:00,986
What the hell happened back there
in those cells, Ted?

1103
01:19:06,659 --> 01:19:08,953
What do you think the weather's like
in Portland, Chuck?

1104
01:19:10,329 --> 01:19:11,455
I'm from Seattle.

1105
01:19:14,583 --> 01:19:15,584
Seattle.

1106
01:19:18,963 --> 01:19:21,757
I'm going on… alone.

1107
01:19:24,718 --> 01:19:27,471
-I'm going with you, boss.
-I said alone.

1108
01:19:29,265 --> 01:19:30,266
Fine.

1109
01:19:35,479 --> 01:19:37,731
[Teddy gasping]

1110
01:19:57,042 --> 01:19:58,043
Damn it!

1111
01:19:59,378 --> 01:20:00,379
Damn it.

1112
01:20:05,968 --> 01:20:09,638
I knew it wouldn't take long,
but I couldn't get to it. The tide was up.

1113
01:20:18,605 --> 01:20:19,606
Chuck!

1114
01:20:22,318 --> 01:20:23,319
Chuck!

1115
01:21:25,130 --> 01:21:26,131
Come on!

1116
01:21:40,813 --> 01:21:42,731
[waves crashing]

1117
01:22:01,708 --> 01:22:02,751
Chuck!

1118
01:22:03,335 --> 01:22:05,254
Where are you, Chuck?

1119
01:22:06,463 --> 01:22:07,589
[rat squeaking]

1120
01:22:10,592 --> 01:22:13,429
[rats squeaking]

1121
01:22:29,903 --> 01:22:30,904
Chuck!

1122
01:22:32,823 --> 01:22:33,824
Chuck!

1123
01:22:39,580 --> 01:22:42,332
[rats squeaking]

1124
01:23:04,730 --> 01:23:08,275
[fire crackling]

1125
01:23:17,618 --> 01:23:19,286
[pants] Who are you?

1126
01:23:21,997 --> 01:23:24,791
I'm Teddy Daniels. I'm a cop.

1127
01:23:26,251 --> 01:23:27,252
You're the Marshal.

1128
01:23:29,004 --> 01:23:30,005
That's right.

1129
01:23:32,758 --> 01:23:36,637
Would you mind taking your hand
from behind your back, please?

1130
01:23:36,762 --> 01:23:39,056
Why? Why? [panting]

1131
01:23:39,973 --> 01:23:42,059
I wanna make sure
that what you're holding won't hurt me.

1132
01:23:50,692 --> 01:23:51,818
I'm gonna keep this…

1133
01:23:53,946 --> 01:23:54,947
if you don't mind.

1134
01:23:56,281 --> 01:23:57,282
[Teddy] Fine by me.

1135
01:24:06,833 --> 01:24:07,834
You're…

1136
01:24:09,419 --> 01:24:10,963
you're Rachel Solando.

1137
01:24:12,881 --> 01:24:13,882
The real one.

1138
01:24:18,220 --> 01:24:19,596
Did you kill your children?

1139
01:24:21,682 --> 01:24:22,891
I never had children.

1140
01:24:24,268 --> 01:24:25,435
I was never married.

1141
01:24:27,563 --> 01:24:30,691
And before I was a patient
at Ashecliffe, I worked here.

1142
01:24:31,733 --> 01:24:34,111
You-- you were a nurse?

1143
01:24:36,655 --> 01:24:38,156
I was a doctor, Marshal.

1144
01:24:42,035 --> 01:24:43,036
You think I'm crazy.

1145
01:24:44,162 --> 01:24:46,748
-No. No, no, I never--
-And if I say I'm not crazy?

1146
01:24:48,625 --> 01:24:49,876
Well, that hardly helps, does it?

1147
01:24:51,920 --> 01:24:53,672
That's the Kafkaesque genius of it.

1148
01:24:57,634 --> 01:24:59,595
People tell the world you're crazy,

1149
01:25:00,095 --> 01:25:03,056
and all your protests to the contrary
just confirm what they're saying.

1150
01:25:04,600 --> 01:25:07,686
I'm-- I'm not following you. I'm sorry.

1151
01:25:08,353 --> 01:25:09,855
Once you're declared insane,

1152
01:25:10,397 --> 01:25:13,775
then anything you do
is called part of that insanity.

1153
01:25:14,026 --> 01:25:16,194
Reasonable protests are denial.

1154
01:25:17,070 --> 01:25:19,656
Valid fears, paranoia.

1155
01:25:19,906 --> 01:25:23,493
Survival instincts
are defense mechanisms.

1156
01:25:24,077 --> 01:25:26,788
You're smarter than you look, Marshal.
That's probably not a good thing.

1157
01:25:28,707 --> 01:25:30,834
-Tell me something.
-Yeah.

1158
01:25:32,544 --> 01:25:33,879
What happened to you?

1159
01:25:35,130 --> 01:25:36,840
I started asking
about these large shipments

1160
01:25:36,923 --> 01:25:40,218
of sodium amytal
and opium-based hallucinogens.

1161
01:25:40,510 --> 01:25:41,845
Psychotropic drugs.

1162
01:25:43,555 --> 01:25:45,015
I asked about the surgeries, too.

1163
01:25:47,976 --> 01:25:49,895
You ever heard of a transorbital lobotomy?

1164
01:25:51,647 --> 01:25:53,440
They zap the patient with electroshock,

1165
01:25:54,483 --> 01:25:56,943
then go through the eye with an ice pick.

1166
01:25:59,488 --> 01:26:00,864
Pull out some nerve fibers.

1167
01:26:02,157 --> 01:26:03,158
Huh.

1168
01:26:03,992 --> 01:26:05,619
Makes the patients much more obedient.

1169
01:26:06,578 --> 01:26:07,579
Tractable.

1170
01:26:09,373 --> 01:26:10,374
It's barbaric.

1171
01:26:11,750 --> 01:26:12,751
Unconscionable.

1172
01:26:14,294 --> 01:26:18,048
Do you know how pain enters the body,
Marshal? Do you?

1173
01:26:19,424 --> 01:26:21,259
-Depends on where you're hurt?
-No.

1174
01:26:22,135 --> 01:26:26,014
It has nothing to do with the flesh.
The brain controls pain.

1175
01:26:26,682 --> 01:26:30,894
The brain controls fear, empathy, sleep,
hunger, anger, everything.

1176
01:26:33,438 --> 01:26:34,690
What if you could control it?

1177
01:26:35,691 --> 01:26:38,819
-You mean, the brain?
-Recreate a man,

1178
01:26:39,444 --> 01:26:41,279
so he doesn't feel pain,

1179
01:26:41,947 --> 01:26:44,032
or love or-- or sympathy.

1180
01:26:45,492 --> 01:26:49,621
A man who can't be interrogated,
because he has no memories to confess.

1181
01:26:52,416 --> 01:26:55,085
You can never take away
all a man's memories.

1182
01:26:55,669 --> 01:26:56,670
-Never.
-Marshal,

1183
01:26:56,753 --> 01:26:59,798
the North Koreans used American POWs,

1184
01:27:00,340 --> 01:27:02,050
during their brainwashing experiments.

1185
01:27:02,134 --> 01:27:05,470
They turned soldiers into traitors.
That's what they're doing here.

1186
01:27:05,595 --> 01:27:07,723
They're creating ghosts
to go out in the world

1187
01:27:07,806 --> 01:27:09,808
and do things sane men--

1188
01:27:09,891 --> 01:27:12,644
-sane men never would.
-To have that kind of ability,

1189
01:27:12,728 --> 01:27:13,729
that kind of knowledge,

1190
01:27:13,812 --> 01:27:16,940
-that-- that would take years.
-Years. Years of research.

1191
01:27:17,190 --> 01:27:19,568
Hundreds of patients to experiment on.

1192
01:27:21,236 --> 01:27:23,697
Fifty years from now,
people will look back

1193
01:27:23,780 --> 01:27:26,908
and say, here, this place,
is where it all began.

1194
01:27:27,784 --> 01:27:30,078
The Nazis used the Jews,
Soviets used prisoners

1195
01:27:30,203 --> 01:27:32,247
in their own Gulags, and we…

1196
01:27:33,457 --> 01:27:36,793
we tested patients… on Shutter Island.

1197
01:27:38,587 --> 01:27:39,713
No, they won't.

1198
01:27:41,089 --> 01:27:42,299
No.

1199
01:27:44,760 --> 01:27:45,886
You do understand…

1200
01:27:49,431 --> 01:27:51,016
that they can't let you leave.

1201
01:27:51,892 --> 01:27:55,270
I am a federal Marshal.
They can't stop me.

1202
01:27:56,563 --> 01:27:58,732
I was an esteemed psychiatrist,

1203
01:28:00,066 --> 01:28:01,735
from a respected family.

1204
01:28:03,862 --> 01:28:04,905
Didn't matter.

1205
01:28:08,200 --> 01:28:09,242
Let me ask you.

1206
01:28:09,826 --> 01:28:11,453
Any past traumas in your life?

1207
01:28:13,580 --> 01:28:14,581
Yes.

1208
01:28:15,957 --> 01:28:17,709
But why-- why would that matter?

1209
01:28:18,043 --> 01:28:20,462
Because they're gonna point
to some event in your past

1210
01:28:20,545 --> 01:28:22,547
and say it's the reason
you lost your sanity.

1211
01:28:23,089 --> 01:28:28,303
So that when they commit you here,
your friends and colleagues will say,

1212
01:28:28,386 --> 01:28:29,721
"Of course, he cracked."

1213
01:28:31,556 --> 01:28:32,891
"Who wouldn't after
what he'd been through?"

1214
01:28:32,974 --> 01:28:35,393
They can say that about anyone,
anyone at all.

1215
01:28:35,477 --> 01:28:37,437
The point is they're gonna say it
about you.

1216
01:28:41,650 --> 01:28:42,692
How's your head?

1217
01:28:43,235 --> 01:28:45,153
My-- my head?

1218
01:28:45,529 --> 01:28:48,740
Any funny dreams lately?
Trouble sleeping?

1219
01:28:51,076 --> 01:28:52,911
-Headaches?
-I--

1220
01:28:53,912 --> 01:28:56,498
-I am prone to migraines, yes.
-Jesus.

1221
01:28:59,125 --> 01:29:02,671
You haven't taken any pills, have you?
I mean, even aspirin?

1222
01:29:02,796 --> 01:29:04,714
-The-- the aspirin?
-Jesus.

1223
01:29:05,549 --> 01:29:07,509
And you-- you ate the food
in the cafeteria,

1224
01:29:07,592 --> 01:29:09,010
and drunk the coffee they gave you?

1225
01:29:09,219 --> 01:29:12,013
You tell me, at least, that
you've been smoking your own cigarettes.

1226
01:29:14,558 --> 01:29:15,559
No.

1227
01:29:16,726 --> 01:29:17,727
No.

1228
01:29:19,020 --> 01:29:20,021
No, I haven't.

1229
01:29:20,230 --> 01:29:23,191
It takes 36 to 48 hours
for neuroleptic narcotics

1230
01:29:23,316 --> 01:29:25,694
to reach workable levels
in the bloodstream.

1231
01:29:27,571 --> 01:29:28,697
Palsy comes first…

1232
01:29:30,323 --> 01:29:32,367
first the fingertips,
then eventually the whole hand.

1233
01:29:34,828 --> 01:29:38,874
Seen any walking nightmares lately,
Marshal, huh?

1234
01:29:41,376 --> 01:29:43,420
Tell me what goes on in that lighthouse.

1235
01:29:45,338 --> 01:29:46,339
Tell me.

1236
01:29:47,799 --> 01:29:48,884
Brain surgery.

1237
01:29:50,093 --> 01:29:52,888
The "Let's open the skull and see
what happens if we pull on this" kind.

1238
01:29:54,931 --> 01:29:56,850
The learned it from the Nazis kind.

1239
01:30:00,061 --> 01:30:01,605
That's where they create the ghosts.

1240
01:30:03,857 --> 01:30:07,611
Who knows about this?
On the island, I mean. Who?

1241
01:30:10,280 --> 01:30:11,281
Everyone.

1242
01:30:11,448 --> 01:30:15,035
Come on. The-- the nurses?
The-- the orderlies?

1243
01:30:15,911 --> 01:30:18,246
-They-- they couldn't possibly know.
-Everyone.

1244
01:30:38,016 --> 01:30:39,100
You can't stay here.

1245
01:30:40,185 --> 01:30:41,436
They think I'm dead, that I drowned.

1246
01:30:41,519 --> 01:30:43,730
I'm afraid if they come looking for you,
they might find me.

1247
01:30:44,648 --> 01:30:46,274
I'm sorry, but you have to go.

1248
01:30:53,573 --> 01:30:54,741
I'm gonna come back for you.

1249
01:30:55,283 --> 01:30:57,994
I won't be here. I move during the day.
New places every night.

1250
01:30:58,370 --> 01:31:00,664
But I could come get you--
get you off this island.

1251
01:31:00,747 --> 01:31:02,499
Haven't you heard a word I've said?

1252
01:31:03,583 --> 01:31:06,753
The only way off the island is the ferry,
and they control it.

1253
01:31:07,837 --> 01:31:08,964
You'll never leave here.

1254
01:31:19,140 --> 01:31:20,183
I had a friend.

1255
01:31:21,059 --> 01:31:23,436
I was with him yesterday,
but we got separated.

1256
01:31:24,646 --> 01:31:25,647
Have you seen him?

1257
01:31:27,524 --> 01:31:28,525
Marshal…

1258
01:31:30,485 --> 01:31:31,611
you have no friends.

1259
01:31:36,449 --> 01:31:37,534
[Teddy groans]

1260
01:31:51,214 --> 01:31:53,675
[birds chirping]

1261
01:32:04,811 --> 01:32:05,979
There you are.

1262
01:32:09,315 --> 01:32:10,942
We were wondering when you'd show up.

1263
01:32:13,486 --> 01:32:14,487
Have a seat.

1264
01:32:15,530 --> 01:32:16,573
Come on.

1265
01:32:27,500 --> 01:32:29,627
Taking a leisurely stroll, were we?

1266
01:32:31,296 --> 01:32:34,132
I was just-- just looking around.

1267
01:32:37,302 --> 01:32:39,012
Did you enjoy God's latest gift?

1268
01:32:41,264 --> 01:32:42,515
-What?
-God's gift.

1269
01:32:44,768 --> 01:32:45,769
The violence.

1270
01:32:48,980 --> 01:32:53,276
When I came downstairs in my home
and I saw that tree in my living room,

1271
01:32:53,359 --> 01:32:57,197
it reached out for me, like a divine hand.

1272
01:32:59,449 --> 01:33:00,867
God loves violence.

1273
01:33:04,037 --> 01:33:06,748
-I-- I hadn't noticed.
-[chuckles] Sure, you have.

1274
01:33:07,916 --> 01:33:09,501
Why else would there be so much of it?

1275
01:33:10,543 --> 01:33:13,004
It's in us. It's what we are.

1276
01:33:15,090 --> 01:33:17,550
We wage war, we burn sacrifices,

1277
01:33:17,634 --> 01:33:20,095
and pillage and plunder and tear
at the flesh of our brothers.

1278
01:33:20,220 --> 01:33:22,806
And why?
Because God gave us violence

1279
01:33:22,889 --> 01:33:24,182
to wage in his honor.

1280
01:33:27,393 --> 01:33:29,354
I thought God gave us moral order.

1281
01:33:29,854 --> 01:33:32,065
There's no moral order
as pure as this storm.

1282
01:33:33,483 --> 01:33:34,943
There's no moral order at all.

1283
01:33:36,069 --> 01:33:39,364
There's just this,
can my violence conquer yours?

1284
01:33:45,286 --> 01:33:46,996
-I'm not violent.
-Yes, you are.

1285
01:33:48,790 --> 01:33:50,333
You're as violent as they come.

1286
01:33:51,835 --> 01:33:54,254
I know this because I'm as violent
as they come.

1287
01:33:55,588 --> 01:33:57,674
If the constraints of society were lifted,

1288
01:33:57,799 --> 01:34:00,468
and I was all that stood
between you and a meal,

1289
01:34:00,552 --> 01:34:03,680
you would crack my skull with a rock
and eat my meaty parts.

1290
01:34:05,849 --> 01:34:06,850
Wouldn't you?

1291
01:34:10,103 --> 01:34:12,647
Cawley thinks you're harmless,
that you can be controlled,

1292
01:34:12,772 --> 01:34:13,815
but I know different.

1293
01:34:15,233 --> 01:34:17,235
-You don't know me.
-Oh, but I do.

1294
01:34:17,318 --> 01:34:19,279
-No, you don't. You don't know me at all.
-I know you.

1295
01:34:20,238 --> 01:34:21,948
We've known each other for centuries.

1296
01:34:32,375 --> 01:34:35,378
If I was to sink my teeth
into your eye right now,

1297
01:34:35,461 --> 01:34:38,089
would you be able to stop me
before I blinded you?

1298
01:34:42,802 --> 01:34:43,803
Give it a try.

1299
01:34:46,014 --> 01:34:47,223
That's the spirit.

1300
01:35:20,548 --> 01:35:22,133
[indistinct chatter]

1301
01:35:22,467 --> 01:35:25,094
[Dr. Cawley] Don't worry because we're
gonna get you back to your room.

1302
01:35:26,763 --> 01:35:28,306
-Not really.
-Something I've seen.

1303
01:35:28,473 --> 01:35:29,474
Okay.

1304
01:35:34,896 --> 01:35:35,897
Where have you been?

1305
01:35:37,148 --> 01:35:39,484
Just wandering.
Just looking at your island.

1306
01:35:39,609 --> 01:35:42,111
Oh, I forgot you're leaving,
now that Rachel's been found.

1307
01:35:44,489 --> 01:35:46,032
-[man] Stop looking at him.
-For sure. Yeah.

1308
01:35:47,158 --> 01:35:48,243
Stop looking at him.

1309
01:35:48,952 --> 01:35:50,787
-Big meeting?
-Oh, yes.

1310
01:35:51,120 --> 01:35:52,538
-It's okay. I'm--
-I don't like that.

1311
01:35:52,664 --> 01:35:56,209
Apparently, there was an unidentified man
in Ward C yesterday.

1312
01:35:56,334 --> 01:35:59,379
He subdued a highly dangerous patient
quite handily.

1313
01:36:00,463 --> 01:36:02,382
-Is that so?
-It seems he had a long conversation

1314
01:36:02,465 --> 01:36:04,759
with a paranoid schizophrenic,
George Noyce.

1315
01:36:05,343 --> 01:36:07,303
[Bridget] Well, I don't remember
what I'm supposed to remember.

1316
01:36:08,054 --> 01:36:09,639
We're gated down. We're fine.

1317
01:36:09,806 --> 01:36:13,601
This-- this Noyce, you said
his name was, he's delusional?

1318
01:36:13,977 --> 01:36:16,145
Extremely. He can be quite upsetting.

1319
01:36:16,688 --> 01:36:18,231
As a matter of fact, two weeks ago,

1320
01:36:18,398 --> 01:36:21,150
a patient got so wound up
by one of Noyce's stories

1321
01:36:21,276 --> 01:36:22,318
that he beat him up.

1322
01:36:23,778 --> 01:36:25,238
-Hmm.
-Cigarette?

1323
01:36:26,114 --> 01:36:27,115
Oh.

1324
01:36:27,490 --> 01:36:28,574
No, thanks. I quit.

1325
01:36:30,326 --> 01:36:34,122
-So you're taking the ferry?
-Yes, absolutely. I…

1326
01:36:34,956 --> 01:36:37,041
I think we've gotten
all we came here for, so…

1327
01:36:37,959 --> 01:36:39,127
"We," Marshal?

1328
01:36:41,379 --> 01:36:42,714
Speaking of which, have you--

1329
01:36:43,673 --> 01:36:45,591
-have you seen him, Doctor?
-Who?

1330
01:36:46,968 --> 01:36:48,177
My partner, Chuck.

1331
01:36:51,055 --> 01:36:53,182
You don't have a partner, Marshal.
You came here alone.

1332
01:36:56,227 --> 01:36:58,521
You know, I've built
something valuable here,

1333
01:36:58,604 --> 01:37:01,774
and valuable things have a way
of being misunderstood in their own time.

1334
01:37:01,858 --> 01:37:03,943
Everyone wants a quick fix.
They always have.

1335
01:37:04,027 --> 01:37:07,739
I'm trying to do something that people,
yourself included, don't understand.

1336
01:37:07,822 --> 01:37:09,907
And I'm not going to give up
without a fight.

1337
01:37:12,535 --> 01:37:13,536
I can see that.

1338
01:37:16,080 --> 01:37:17,081
Hmm.

1339
01:37:18,291 --> 01:37:19,751
So, tell me again about your partner.

1340
01:37:22,587 --> 01:37:23,588
What partner?

1341
01:37:24,964 --> 01:37:26,424
-[indistinct]
-[laughs]

1342
01:37:27,133 --> 01:37:28,134
It's fine.

1343
01:37:31,554 --> 01:37:32,555
[scoffs]

1344
01:37:40,521 --> 01:37:43,232
[music playing faintly]

1345
01:38:16,349 --> 01:38:19,811
[man] She made a mess. I cleaned it up.
She made a mess again.

1346
01:38:29,487 --> 01:38:30,488
Marshal.

1347
01:38:32,115 --> 01:38:33,157
Going somewhere?

1348
01:38:34,033 --> 01:38:35,326
I'm just-- just

1349
01:38:35,868 --> 01:38:37,620
-heading out to the ferry, so…
-Ah.

1350
01:38:38,037 --> 01:38:40,790
Well, I'm afraid,
I'm afraid it's the other way.

1351
01:38:42,166 --> 01:38:43,167
Oh.

1352
01:38:44,252 --> 01:38:45,962
If you'll wait a moment, I'll…

1353
01:38:46,838 --> 01:38:49,006
find you someone
who can take you to the dock.

1354
01:38:53,553 --> 01:38:57,390
-What's this, Doctor, huh? What's this?
-It's-- it's just a sedative.

1355
01:38:57,682 --> 01:39:00,351
-A precaution.
-Oh, precaution.

1356
01:39:03,813 --> 01:39:07,150
What are you going to do?
Kill me? Marshal.

1357
01:39:08,067 --> 01:39:09,527
You think you deserve it?

1358
01:39:09,777 --> 01:39:12,697
For what, hmm? Provoking you?

1359
01:39:13,364 --> 01:39:16,200
Well, forgive me.
What doesn't provoke you?

1360
01:39:16,742 --> 01:39:19,787
-Remarks? Words?
-Nazis?

1361
01:39:20,329 --> 01:39:21,330
Well, that, too.

1362
01:39:22,331 --> 01:39:24,333
And, of course, memories and dreams.

1363
01:39:25,376 --> 01:39:29,755
Did you know that the word trauma comes
from the Greek "for wound"?

1364
01:39:30,381 --> 01:39:32,383
And what is the German word for dream?

1365
01:39:33,217 --> 01:39:35,344
[speaking German]

1366
01:39:36,804 --> 01:39:39,724
Wounds can create monsters, and you,

1367
01:39:40,349 --> 01:39:42,727
you are wounded, Marshal.

1368
01:39:43,769 --> 01:39:46,606
And wouldn't you agree,
when you see a monster,

1369
01:39:47,648 --> 01:39:48,816
you must stop it?

1370
01:39:50,109 --> 01:39:51,110
Yeah.

1371
01:39:52,361 --> 01:39:53,529
-I agree.
-Yes.

1372
01:39:55,031 --> 01:39:56,032
Yeah.

1373
01:39:56,282 --> 01:39:57,283
[muffled screams]

1374
01:40:13,299 --> 01:40:15,301
[guard] I told him that we'd take
about an hour to do it.

1375
01:40:15,426 --> 01:40:16,332
Yeah.

1376
01:40:16,432 --> 01:40:18,304
[guard 1] Did they say
we're going to do the first floor?

1377
01:40:18,804 --> 01:40:20,056
[guard] How long you been on the clock?

1378
01:40:20,223 --> 01:40:23,768
-I've been on for 18 hours straight.
-[guard] Nice paycheck.

1379
01:40:40,952 --> 01:40:42,286
[Dolores] What are you doing, baby?

1380
01:40:47,875 --> 01:40:50,086
-You gotta get to the ferry.
-No.

1381
01:40:51,337 --> 01:40:52,338
No, no.

1382
01:40:53,673 --> 01:40:54,674
Yeah.

1383
01:40:55,967 --> 01:41:00,012
If the world thinks that Chuck is dead,
then he's perfect for their experiments.

1384
01:41:01,931 --> 01:41:03,474
There's only one place they'd take him.

1385
01:41:06,978 --> 01:41:08,020
You go there, and you'll die.

1386
01:41:08,354 --> 01:41:10,189
He's my partner.
If they are hurting him,

1387
01:41:10,273 --> 01:41:12,650
if they're holding him against his will,
I've gotta bring him out.

1388
01:41:13,526 --> 01:41:14,652
I can't lose anyone else.

1389
01:41:15,695 --> 01:41:16,821
Don't go, Teddy, please.

1390
01:41:17,446 --> 01:41:19,240
-[echoes] Please, don't do this. Don't go.
-I'm sorry, honey.

1391
01:41:24,036 --> 01:41:25,037
I'm sorry, honey.

1392
01:41:26,831 --> 01:41:28,958
I love this thing
because you gave it to me.

1393
01:41:32,503 --> 01:41:33,504
The truth is…

1394
01:41:35,840 --> 01:41:37,550
it's one fucking ugly tie.

1395
01:42:18,215 --> 01:42:19,216
No.

1396
01:43:40,381 --> 01:43:41,382
[grunts]

1397
01:43:41,465 --> 01:43:42,591
Don't move! Stay where you are!

1398
01:43:44,719 --> 01:43:46,011
Are you gonna kill me?

1399
01:43:47,722 --> 01:43:49,932
No, I'm not gonna kill you.

1400
01:43:52,017 --> 01:43:53,185
-[loud thud]
-[guard grunts]

1401
01:45:42,878 --> 01:45:44,338
Why are you all wet, baby?

1402
01:45:46,924 --> 01:45:49,218
-What did you say?
-You know exactly what I said.

1403
01:46:03,274 --> 01:46:04,900
The rifle's empty, by the way.

1404
01:46:12,074 --> 01:46:13,075
Have a seat.

1405
01:46:20,082 --> 01:46:22,459
For God's sake, dry off.
You'll catch a cold.

1406
01:46:24,086 --> 01:46:25,087
All right.

1407
01:46:28,841 --> 01:46:30,551
How badly did you hurt the guard?

1408
01:46:32,469 --> 01:46:34,972
I-- I don't know
what you're talking about.

1409
01:46:38,434 --> 01:46:39,560
Yes, he's here.

1410
01:46:40,477 --> 01:46:43,397
Have Dr. Sheehan take a look at your man
before you send him up.

1411
01:46:44,690 --> 01:46:45,691
So…

1412
01:46:46,692 --> 01:46:49,320
Dr. Sheehan came in
on the ferry this morning, huh?

1413
01:46:50,446 --> 01:46:51,447
Not exactly.

1414
01:46:53,073 --> 01:46:55,326
You blew up my car.
I really loved that car.

1415
01:46:56,911 --> 01:46:58,245
Sorry to hear about that.

1416
01:47:02,291 --> 01:47:03,375
Tremors are getting pretty bad.

1417
01:47:05,252 --> 01:47:06,462
How are the hallucinations?

1418
01:47:07,838 --> 01:47:08,923
[Dolores] Get out of here, Teddy.

1419
01:47:10,132 --> 01:47:11,884
This place is gonna be the end of you.

1420
01:47:15,846 --> 01:47:17,723
-Not bad.
-They'll get worse.

1421
01:47:18,807 --> 01:47:19,808
I know.

1422
01:47:20,225 --> 01:47:21,644
Dr. Solando…

1423
01:47:22,895 --> 01:47:24,647
she told me about the neuroleptics.

1424
01:47:25,230 --> 01:47:27,608
Did she, now? And when was this?

1425
01:47:27,816 --> 01:47:30,235
I found her, Doctor, in a cave…

1426
01:47:30,736 --> 01:47:33,614
out by the cliffs.
But, you'll never get to her.

1427
01:47:33,906 --> 01:47:34,907
I don't doubt it…

1428
01:47:36,116 --> 01:47:37,576
considering she's not real.

1429
01:47:39,870 --> 01:47:41,956
Your delusions are more severe
than I thought.

1430
01:47:44,166 --> 01:47:45,459
You're not on neuroleptics.

1431
01:47:46,710 --> 01:47:48,504
You're not on anything,
as a matter of fact.

1432
01:47:48,629 --> 01:47:51,256
Then what the fuck is this?
Huh? What the fuck is this?

1433
01:47:51,423 --> 01:47:52,424
Withdrawal.

1434
01:47:52,967 --> 01:47:54,134
With-- withdrawal?

1435
01:47:54,677 --> 01:47:56,261
From, from what?
I haven't had a goddamn drink

1436
01:47:56,345 --> 01:47:57,721
since I've been on this island.

1437
01:47:57,846 --> 01:47:58,847
Chlorpromazine.

1438
01:48:00,391 --> 01:48:03,394
I'm not a fan of pharmacology,
but I have to say, in your case…

1439
01:48:04,019 --> 01:48:06,689
-Chlo-- chloraproma what?
-Chlorpromazine.

1440
01:48:07,398 --> 01:48:11,235
The same thing we've been giving you
for the past 24 months.

1441
01:48:13,153 --> 01:48:14,613
So for the past two years, you--

1442
01:48:14,697 --> 01:48:18,033
you've had somebody slipping me drugs
in Boston, is that it?

1443
01:48:18,200 --> 01:48:19,284
Not Boston.

1444
01:48:20,244 --> 01:48:21,245
Here.

1445
01:48:22,246 --> 01:48:26,375
You've been here for two years.
A patient of this institution.

1446
01:48:30,045 --> 01:48:31,880
After everything I've seen here, doctor,

1447
01:48:32,881 --> 01:48:36,385
you-- you really think
you're gonna convince me I'm crazy, huh?

1448
01:48:37,136 --> 01:48:39,263
Do you know the kind of people
that I deal with every day?

1449
01:48:39,346 --> 01:48:41,140
I'm a U.S. Marshal, for God's sakes.

1450
01:48:41,223 --> 01:48:43,142
You were a U.S. Marshal.

1451
01:48:43,225 --> 01:48:47,062
Here's a copy of the intake form.
You broke into Ward C-4.

1452
01:48:47,187 --> 01:48:49,857
Proof of the 67th patient.
If you'd gotten it to the mainland,

1453
01:48:49,940 --> 01:48:51,564
you could have blown
the lid off this place.

1454
01:48:51,650 --> 01:48:53,014
-Wait. Where did-- Where did you--
-Yet somehow,

1455
01:48:53,235 --> 01:48:55,946
you couldn't find time to look at it.
Well, read it now.

1456
01:48:56,905 --> 01:48:57,906
Go ahead.

1457
01:49:02,161 --> 01:49:05,456
"Patient is highly intelligent,
highly delusional decorated Army veteran."

1458
01:49:05,998 --> 01:49:08,792
"Present for the liber--
Liberation of Dachau."

1459
01:49:09,918 --> 01:49:12,629
"F-- Former U.S. Marshal."
"Known proclivity for violence."

1460
01:49:12,713 --> 01:49:13,922
"Shows no remorse for his crime

1461
01:49:14,006 --> 01:49:16,759
because he denies the crime ever,
ever took place."

1462
01:49:16,925 --> 01:49:18,969
"Highly developed
and fantastical narratives,

1463
01:49:19,053 --> 01:49:21,472
which preclude facing the truth
of his actions."

1464
01:49:21,722 --> 01:49:24,099
I've had enough of this bullshit!
Where's-- where's my partner, huh?

1465
01:49:24,308 --> 01:49:25,642
Where's Chuck? Where is he?

1466
01:49:26,643 --> 01:49:28,062
Let's try this another way.

1467
01:49:28,395 --> 01:49:30,647
Your wife's maiden name was Chanal,
am I correct?

1468
01:49:30,856 --> 01:49:32,274
Don't you even talk about her.

1469
01:49:32,399 --> 01:49:33,609
-Don't you--
-I'm afraid I have to.

1470
01:49:36,445 --> 01:49:38,489
{\an8}Notice anything these four names
have in common?

1471
01:49:38,947 --> 01:49:40,199
{\an8}It's your rule of four.

1472
01:49:40,824 --> 01:49:41,825
Andrew, what do you see?

1473
01:49:41,909 --> 01:49:44,828
If you've done anything to my partner,
Doctor, that is a violation of--

1474
01:49:45,120 --> 01:49:46,997
Focus, Andrew! What do you see?

1475
01:49:48,540 --> 01:49:50,793
The names have the same letters.

1476
01:49:52,086 --> 01:49:55,297
{\an8}Edward Daniels has exactly
the same 13 letters as Andrew Laeddis.

1477
01:49:55,506 --> 01:49:57,716
{\an8}The same as Rachel Solando
and Dolores Chanal.

1478
01:49:57,800 --> 01:49:59,551
{\an8}The names are anagrams
for each other.

1479
01:49:59,843 --> 01:50:01,178
Your tactics,

1480
01:50:01,512 --> 01:50:03,889
-they're-- they're not gonna work on me.
-You came here for the truth.

1481
01:50:04,264 --> 01:50:05,265
Here it is.

1482
01:50:05,432 --> 01:50:07,309
Your name is Andrew Laeddis.

1483
01:50:07,518 --> 01:50:10,521
The 67th patient at Ashecliffe
is you, Andrew.

1484
01:50:13,232 --> 01:50:14,608
-Bullshit.
-You were committed here

1485
01:50:14,691 --> 01:50:16,235
by court order 24 months ago.

1486
01:50:16,318 --> 01:50:19,613
Your crime is terrible,
one you can't forgive yourself for,

1487
01:50:19,696 --> 01:50:21,532
so you invented another self.

1488
01:50:24,243 --> 01:50:25,244
All right.

1489
01:50:26,745 --> 01:50:28,497
Let's-- let's get down to the facts,

1490
01:50:28,580 --> 01:50:30,457
-all right?
-You've created a story

1491
01:50:30,541 --> 01:50:31,750
in which you're not a murderer.

1492
01:50:31,875 --> 01:50:33,794
You're a hero, still a U.S. Marshal,

1493
01:50:33,961 --> 01:50:35,879
only here at Ashecliffe
because of a case,

1494
01:50:36,004 --> 01:50:39,216
and you've uncovered a conspiracy
so that anything we tell you

1495
01:50:39,299 --> 01:50:40,926
about who you are, what you've done,

1496
01:50:41,260 --> 01:50:43,220
you can dismiss as lies, Andrew.

1497
01:50:43,387 --> 01:50:44,888
My name is Edward Daniels.

1498
01:50:45,013 --> 01:50:48,642
I've been hearing this fantasy
for two years now. I know every detail.

1499
01:50:49,017 --> 01:50:50,894
Patient 67, the storm,

1500
01:50:51,061 --> 01:50:54,231
Rachel Solando, your missing partner,
the dreams you have every night.

1501
01:50:54,356 --> 01:50:56,817
You were at Dachau,
but you may not have killed any guards.

1502
01:50:58,569 --> 01:50:59,570
[sighs]

1503
01:51:00,821 --> 01:51:03,740
I wish I could let you just live
in your fantasy world.

1504
01:51:04,366 --> 01:51:05,367
I really do.

1505
01:51:07,077 --> 01:51:08,495
But you're violent, trained,

1506
01:51:08,745 --> 01:51:10,747
dangerous. You're the most dangerous
patient we have.

1507
01:51:11,582 --> 01:51:13,834
You've injured orderlies, guards,
other patients.

1508
01:51:13,959 --> 01:51:15,878
Two weeks ago,
you attacked George Noyce.

1509
01:51:16,003 --> 01:51:18,005
No, no. I am fucking on to you, Doctor.

1510
01:51:18,297 --> 01:51:20,132
-You had Noyce beaten.
-Of course I didn't!

1511
01:51:20,340 --> 01:51:22,134
Give me one reason
why I would even touch him!

1512
01:51:22,384 --> 01:51:24,011
Because he called you Laeddis,

1513
01:51:24,845 --> 01:51:27,055
and you'd do anything not to be him.

1514
01:51:28,015 --> 01:51:31,560
I have a transcript of the conversation
you had with Noyce yesterday.

1515
01:51:31,685 --> 01:51:35,480
"This is about you, and Laeddis,
that's all it's ever been about."

1516
01:51:37,649 --> 01:51:40,235
No, no.
He's saying this is about me and Laeddis.

1517
01:51:40,319 --> 01:51:42,154
When you asked him
what happened to his face,

1518
01:51:42,237 --> 01:51:45,115
he said, now here I'm quoting again,
"You did this."

1519
01:51:45,699 --> 01:51:49,286
-No, no, he meant that it was my fault.
-You almost killed him.

1520
01:51:51,538 --> 01:51:54,333
The warden and the Board of Overseers
are determined something be done.

1521
01:51:54,416 --> 01:51:55,417
It's been decided,

1522
01:51:56,168 --> 01:52:00,047
that unless we can bring you back
to sanity now, right now,

1523
01:52:00,923 --> 01:52:04,259
permanent measures will be taken to ensure
you can't hurt anyone ever again.

1524
01:52:07,804 --> 01:52:09,223
They'll lobotomize you, Andrew.

1525
01:52:10,140 --> 01:52:11,141
Do you understand?

1526
01:52:15,479 --> 01:52:16,563
Yeah, I understand.

1527
01:52:18,273 --> 01:52:19,650
I-- I understand just fine.

1528
01:52:21,068 --> 01:52:24,571
If I-- if I don't play along
with your little game here,

1529
01:52:25,113 --> 01:52:27,783
Dr. Naehring's gonna turn me
into one of his ghosts.

1530
01:52:28,700 --> 01:52:29,993
But what about my partner?

1531
01:52:30,244 --> 01:52:32,162
You-- you're gonna tell
the U.S. Marshal's office

1532
01:52:32,329 --> 01:52:33,914
that he's a defense mechanism?

1533
01:52:36,583 --> 01:52:37,584
Hello, boss.

1534
01:52:54,977 --> 01:52:57,521
What-- what the fuck is going on here?

1535
01:52:59,106 --> 01:53:00,107
Huh?

1536
01:53:02,859 --> 01:53:04,194
You-- are you working for him?

1537
01:53:05,028 --> 01:53:06,613
I'm sorry. There wasn't any other way.

1538
01:53:06,738 --> 01:53:08,782
Someone had to stick with you,
keep you safe.

1539
01:53:12,494 --> 01:53:13,704
You been watching me, huh?

1540
01:53:15,539 --> 01:53:16,707
Watching me every minute.

1541
01:53:18,500 --> 01:53:19,710
Who, who are you?

1542
01:53:20,544 --> 01:53:21,628
Who are you? Tell me.

1543
01:53:22,254 --> 01:53:23,922
Don't you recognize me, Andrew?

1544
01:53:25,716 --> 01:53:28,510
I've been your primary psychiatrist
for the last two years.

1545
01:53:30,012 --> 01:53:31,221
I'm Lester Sheehan.

1546
01:53:38,395 --> 01:53:40,022
I told you-- I told you about my wife,

1547
01:53:40,105 --> 01:53:41,106
-I--
-I know.

1548
01:53:41,189 --> 01:53:44,276
I climbed down a cliff to get you.
I-- I trusted you.

1549
01:53:44,359 --> 01:53:47,195
I-- I risked everything
to come in here after you.

1550
01:53:47,279 --> 01:53:48,947
-Everything!
-I know, boss.

1551
01:53:49,281 --> 01:53:50,741
We're running out of time here, Andrew.

1552
01:53:52,367 --> 01:53:54,077
I swore before the Board of Overseers

1553
01:53:54,161 --> 01:53:58,707
that I could construct the most radical,
cutting-edge role-play ever attempted

1554
01:53:58,790 --> 01:54:00,375
in psychiatry,
and it would bring you back.

1555
01:54:00,459 --> 01:54:02,669
I thought that if we let you play
this out,

1556
01:54:03,545 --> 01:54:06,548
we could get you to see how untrue,
how impossible it is.

1557
01:54:08,216 --> 01:54:10,010
You've had the run of the place
for two days.

1558
01:54:10,802 --> 01:54:13,472
Tell me, where are the Nazi experiments?

1559
01:54:14,264 --> 01:54:15,557
The satanic ORs?

1560
01:54:29,613 --> 01:54:31,281
[Chuck] Andrew, listen to me.

1561
01:54:33,867 --> 01:54:35,118
If we fail with you,

1562
01:54:36,286 --> 01:54:38,580
then everything that we've tried
to do here will be discredited.

1563
01:54:38,663 --> 01:54:39,664
Everything.

1564
01:54:42,250 --> 01:54:44,419
We're on the front lines
of a war here, old boy.

1565
01:54:46,254 --> 01:54:48,465
And right now, it all comes down to you.

1566
01:54:56,014 --> 01:54:58,433
-Don't move! Don't move!
-Andrew! Andrew! No.

1567
01:54:58,642 --> 01:55:01,103
-No.
-My name is Edward Daniels!

1568
01:55:02,104 --> 01:55:04,231
This one's loaded.
I can tell by the weight.

1569
01:55:04,314 --> 01:55:06,525
I see. And that's your firearm, Marshal?
You're sure?

1570
01:55:06,900 --> 01:55:08,193
My initials are on the side!

1571
01:55:08,276 --> 01:55:10,529
There's a dent in the barrel
from when Philip Stacks shot at me.

1572
01:55:10,612 --> 01:55:12,697
You're not gonna fuck with my mind
on this one, doctor!

1573
01:55:12,781 --> 01:55:13,782
[Dr. Cawley] Then blast away.

1574
01:55:13,949 --> 01:55:16,118
Because that's the only way
you're ever getting off this island.

1575
01:55:19,246 --> 01:55:20,247
[metal clanking]

1576
01:55:23,333 --> 01:55:24,709
Andrew, please, don't.

1577
01:55:36,221 --> 01:55:37,222
My gun.

1578
01:55:44,396 --> 01:55:45,856
What did you do to my goddamn gun?

1579
01:55:46,898 --> 01:55:48,066
It's a toy, Andrew.

1580
01:55:51,653 --> 01:55:53,029
We're telling you the truth.

1581
01:55:54,197 --> 01:55:57,492
Dolores was insane,
manic-depressive, suicidal.

1582
01:55:58,118 --> 01:56:01,246
You drank, stayed away,
ignored what everyone told you.

1583
01:56:01,413 --> 01:56:02,497
You moved to that lake house

1584
01:56:02,581 --> 01:56:05,584
after she purposely
set your city apartment on fire.

1585
01:56:05,709 --> 01:56:07,002
-You were--
-You're lying.

1586
01:56:07,127 --> 01:56:09,296
-[Dr. Cawley] Andrew! Andrew, stop. No.
-You drugged the cigarettes!

1587
01:56:10,672 --> 01:56:12,466
-[Teddy] All you've done is lie!
-Andrew. Andrew.

1588
01:56:12,549 --> 01:56:14,634
Your children. Andrew, your children.

1589
01:56:15,886 --> 01:56:16,887
Simon.

1590
01:56:17,762 --> 01:56:19,890
-Henry.
-I never had any children.

1591
01:56:20,515 --> 01:56:21,766
Your wife drowned them,

1592
01:56:22,434 --> 01:56:24,102
at the cabin by the lake.

1593
01:56:24,436 --> 01:56:27,564
And here, the little girl,
the one you dream of,

1594
01:56:28,315 --> 01:56:29,316
every night.

1595
01:56:30,150 --> 01:56:31,234
I never had a little girl.

1596
01:56:31,318 --> 01:56:34,196
The one who tells you over and over
that you should have saved her,

1597
01:56:34,988 --> 01:56:36,156
saved them all.

1598
01:56:36,990 --> 01:56:41,953
Your daughter, her name was Rachel.
Are you going to deny that she ever lived?

1599
01:56:43,163 --> 01:56:44,331
Andrew, are you?

1600
01:57:08,188 --> 01:57:09,397
[Dolores] I'm so sorry, baby.

1601
01:57:14,611 --> 01:57:16,446
I told you not to come in here.

1602
01:57:17,405 --> 01:57:21,201
I told you, this would be the end of you.

1603
01:57:41,555 --> 01:57:42,556
I'm back!

1604
01:57:43,515 --> 01:57:45,600
We got him just outside of Oklahoma.

1605
01:57:46,309 --> 01:57:48,853
Must've stopped ten places
in between here and Tulsa.

1606
01:57:48,937 --> 01:57:50,272
I could sleep for a week.

1607
01:57:50,522 --> 01:57:53,066
[music playing on record player]

1608
01:57:55,110 --> 01:57:56,111
Dolores?

1609
01:58:03,243 --> 01:58:04,244
Dolores?

1610
01:58:09,332 --> 01:58:11,459
[man] <i>And he said, "Take up your bed</i>
<i>and walk." But God?</i>

1611
01:58:11,543 --> 01:58:12,424
[Teddy] Dolores?

1612
01:58:12,590 --> 01:58:13,945
<i>…Then he said,</i>
<i>"Take up your bed and walk."</i>

1613
01:58:14,051 --> 01:58:15,380
<i>Forgive sins, but God?</i>

1614
01:58:27,350 --> 01:58:28,351
Dolores?

1615
01:58:53,918 --> 01:58:54,919
Baby.

1616
01:58:57,213 --> 01:58:58,340
Why are you all wet?

1617
01:59:01,384 --> 01:59:02,385
I missed you.

1618
01:59:10,352 --> 01:59:11,603
I wanna go home.

1619
01:59:15,106 --> 01:59:16,107
You are home.

1620
01:59:21,821 --> 01:59:22,947
Where are the kids?

1621
01:59:25,825 --> 01:59:26,826
Huh?

1622
01:59:27,744 --> 01:59:28,745
They're in school.

1623
01:59:33,708 --> 01:59:35,585
It's Saturday, honey.

1624
01:59:36,836 --> 01:59:38,421
School's not in on Saturday.

1625
01:59:41,675 --> 01:59:43,176
My school is.

1626
01:59:47,722 --> 01:59:50,308
[birds chirping]

1627
01:59:56,606 --> 01:59:57,941
Oh, my God.

1628
02:00:00,402 --> 02:00:01,528
Oh, my God!

1629
02:00:15,083 --> 02:00:17,669
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

1630
02:00:20,213 --> 02:00:21,214
Ah!

1631
02:00:21,923 --> 02:00:23,174
Oh, my God. No!

1632
02:00:27,887 --> 02:00:28,888
Come on, come on.

1633
02:00:39,274 --> 02:00:41,067
[groans]

1634
02:00:42,944 --> 02:00:45,989
No. No. Please, God.

1635
02:00:48,074 --> 02:00:49,659
Please, God. No!

1636
02:00:49,826 --> 02:00:53,788
No! [wailing]

1637
02:00:54,956 --> 02:00:56,082
No.

1638
02:00:56,458 --> 02:00:58,042
[crying]

1639
02:01:01,504 --> 02:01:02,505
No.

1640
02:01:05,258 --> 02:01:06,259
No.

1641
02:01:11,139 --> 02:01:12,390
[crying]

1642
02:01:50,970 --> 02:01:51,971
Baby.

1643
02:02:11,115 --> 02:02:12,534
Let's put them at the table, Andrew.

1644
02:02:14,410 --> 02:02:17,580
We'll dry them off.
We'll change their clothes.

1645
02:02:19,666 --> 02:02:22,085
They'll be our living dolls. Huh.

1646
02:02:26,047 --> 02:02:27,757
Tomorrow, we can take them on a picnic.

1647
02:02:33,847 --> 02:02:38,518
If you ever loved me, Dolores,
please stop talking.

1648
02:02:45,066 --> 02:02:46,150
I love you.

1649
02:02:55,243 --> 02:02:56,870
Set me free.

1650
02:03:01,499 --> 02:03:02,876
Oh, baby.

1651
02:03:06,254 --> 02:03:07,881
We'll give them baths.

1652
02:03:11,509 --> 02:03:14,679
-I love you, baby.
-I love you, too.

1653
02:03:14,929 --> 02:03:16,639
-I love you so much.
-I love you so much.

1654
02:03:16,723 --> 02:03:18,474
-I love you. I--
-[gunshot fires]

1655
02:03:42,165 --> 02:03:43,791
[crying] Oh, baby.

1656
02:03:49,881 --> 02:03:50,882
Andrew.

1657
02:03:52,967 --> 02:03:54,302
Andrew, can you hear me?

1658
02:03:55,720 --> 02:03:56,721
[Teddy] Rachel.

1659
02:03:57,972 --> 02:03:59,182
Rachel, Rachel.

1660
02:04:01,809 --> 02:04:02,810
Rachel?

1661
02:04:05,605 --> 02:04:06,606
[Chuck] Rachel who?

1662
02:04:10,360 --> 02:04:11,527
Rachel. Rachel Laeddis.

1663
02:04:13,112 --> 02:04:14,113
My, my daughter.

1664
02:04:18,493 --> 02:04:19,535
Why are you here?

1665
02:04:21,621 --> 02:04:22,622
[whispers] Because…

1666
02:04:23,373 --> 02:04:26,417
-Because I killed my wife.
-And why did you do that?

1667
02:04:32,131 --> 02:04:33,841
Because she murdered our children.

1668
02:04:36,636 --> 02:04:38,137
And she told me to let her go.

1669
02:04:42,308 --> 02:04:45,436
-Who's Teddy Daniels?
-He doesn't exist.

1670
02:04:47,939 --> 02:04:49,899
Neither does Rachel Solando.
I made them up.

1671
02:04:50,441 --> 02:04:51,442
Why?

1672
02:04:53,069 --> 02:04:54,445
We need to hear you say it.

1673
02:05:01,077 --> 02:05:03,621
After she tried to kill herself
the first time…

1674
02:05:06,249 --> 02:05:07,583
Dolores told me she…

1675
02:05:09,460 --> 02:05:10,712
she had an insect…

1676
02:05:11,963 --> 02:05:13,381
living inside her brain.

1677
02:05:15,550 --> 02:05:16,759
She could feel it…

1678
02:05:18,594 --> 02:05:20,346
clicking across her skull, just…

1679
02:05:22,390 --> 02:05:24,434
pulling the wires, just for fun.

1680
02:05:28,104 --> 02:05:29,397
She told me that.

1681
02:05:31,441 --> 02:05:32,900
She told me that, but I didn't listen.

1682
02:05:37,989 --> 02:05:39,532
I loved her so much, you know?

1683
02:05:41,492 --> 02:05:42,785
[Dr. Cawley] Why did you make them up?

1684
02:05:46,080 --> 02:05:48,708
Because I can't take knowing
that Dolores killed our children.

1685
02:05:53,713 --> 02:05:54,714
And I…

1686
02:05:57,467 --> 02:06:01,721
I killed them 'cause I didn't,
I didn't get her help, you know?

1687
02:06:06,350 --> 02:06:07,351
I killed them.

1688
02:06:12,648 --> 02:06:15,568
Here's my fear, Andrew.
We-- we broke through once before,

1689
02:06:16,319 --> 02:06:18,154
nine months ago, and then you regressed.

1690
02:06:21,657 --> 02:06:24,077
-I don't remember that.
-I know.

1691
02:06:25,578 --> 02:06:26,788
You reset, Andrew.

1692
02:06:27,747 --> 02:06:31,459
Like a tape playing over and over
on an endless loop.

1693
02:06:33,002 --> 02:06:34,545
I hope that what we've done here
will be enough

1694
02:06:34,629 --> 02:06:36,672
to stop it from ever happening again,
but…

1695
02:06:37,840 --> 02:06:41,052
I need to know you've accepted reality.

1696
02:06:47,892 --> 02:06:49,769
You-- you came after me, huh, doctor?

1697
02:06:52,605 --> 02:06:56,400
You-- you tried to help me
when no one else would.

1698
02:07:08,788 --> 02:07:10,164
My name's Andrew Laeddis…

1699
02:07:18,047 --> 02:07:21,384
and I murdered my wife
in the spring of '52.

1700
02:07:46,200 --> 02:07:49,328
-How we doing this morning?
-Good.

1701
02:07:49,829 --> 02:07:52,248
-And you?
-Can't complain.

1702
02:08:02,592 --> 02:08:06,220
-So what's our next move?
-You tell me.

1703
02:08:12,018 --> 02:08:13,686
We gotta get off this rock, Chuck.

1704
02:08:15,313 --> 02:08:16,314
Get back to the mainland.

1705
02:08:16,439 --> 02:08:18,441
Whatever the hell's going on here,
it's bad.

1706
02:08:34,248 --> 02:08:35,333
[inaudible]

1707
02:08:41,088 --> 02:08:43,132
Don't worry, partner,
they're not gonna catch us.

1708
02:08:50,056 --> 02:08:51,766
That's right. We're too smart for them.

1709
02:08:54,018 --> 02:08:55,228
Yeah, we are, aren't we?

1710
02:09:11,911 --> 02:09:13,663
You know, this place makes me wonder.

1711
02:09:14,997 --> 02:09:16,290
Yeah, what's that, boss?

1712
02:09:18,084 --> 02:09:19,418
Which would be worse…

1713
02:09:20,878 --> 02:09:22,421
to live as a monster…

1714
02:09:23,589 --> 02:09:25,091
or to die as a good man?

1715
02:09:34,850 --> 02:09:35,851
Teddy?

1716
02:12:31,652 --> 02:12:36,365
["This Bitter Earth"
by Dinah Washington plays]

1717
02:12:59,054 --> 02:13:02,057
